{"title_page": "George Okill Stuart Jr.", "text_new": "{{other people|George Stuart|George Stuart (disambiguation)}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = George Okill Stuart Jr.\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = George Okill Stuart.jpg\n| order            = 3rd \n| office           = Mayor of Quebec City\n| predecessor      = [[Ren\u00e9-\u00c9douard Caron]]\n| successor        = [[Narcisse-Fortunat Belleau]] \n| term_start       = 1846\n| term_end         = 1850\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1807|10|12}}\n| birth_place      = York (Toronto), Upper Canada\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1884|3|5|1807|10|12}}\n| death_place      = Quebec City, Quebec\n| resting_place    = [[Mount Hermon Cemetery]], [[Sillery, Quebec City|Sillery]], Quebec \n| nationality      = \n| spouse           = \n| party            = \n| relations        = [[George Okill Stuart (clergyman)|George Okill Stuart]], father\n| children         = \n| residence        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| religion         = \n}}\n'''George Okill Stuart''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|QC}} (October 12, 1807 &ndash; March 5, 1884) was an Anglo-[[Quebec]] lawyer, judge and political figure.\n\nHe was born in (York, later [[Toronto]]), [[Upper Canada]] in 1807, the son of [[George Okill Stuart]] and was educated at [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]] and [[Quebec City]]. He articled in law with his uncle, [[James Stuart (Lower Canada statesman)|James Stuart]], and was admitted to the Lower Canada Bar in 1830. He entered practice with his uncle from 1834 until 1838, when his uncle became chief justice for [[Lower Canada]]. Stuart served as solicitor for the city of Quebec from 1841 to 1843. In 1843, he was elected to city council and he served as mayor from 1846 to 1850. In 1851, he was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of the Province of Canada]] for Quebec City as an independent Conservative. He was defeated in 1854 but reelected in an 1857 by-election. Stuart was b\u00e2tonnier for the bar of Lower Canada from 1851 to 1853. In 1854, he was named [[Queen's Counsel]]. He was an assistant judge in the Superior Court of Lower Canada for a short time in 1855. Stuart served as a director for the Saint Maurice Railway and Navigation Company. He started a law firm with John Murphy around 1861 that operated until 1873. In 1873, he became an assistant to [[Henry Black (Quebec judge)|Henry Black]], a judge in the [[Vice admiralty court|Vice Admiralty Court]] at Quebec; when Black died later that year, Stuart was chosen as his replacement and served in that function until his death at Quebec City in 1884.\n\nStuart also published a volume of case reports from the courts of King's Bench, the provincial Court of Appeals of Lower Canada and the Court of Vice Admiralty and edited another work on cases related to maritime law.\n\n==External links==\n* {{QuebecMNAbio|stuart-george-okill-5421}}\n*{{Cite DCB|5855}}\n*{{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{Mayor of Quebec City}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stuart, George Okill}}\n[[Category:1807 births]]\n[[Category:1884 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Legislative Assembly of the Province of Canada]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Quebec City]]\n[[Category:Judges in Quebec]]\n[[Category:United Empire Loyalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Canadian Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:Burials at Mount Hermon Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|George Stuart|George Stuart (disambiguation)}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = George Okill Stuart Jr.\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image            = George Okill Stuart.jpg\n| order            = 3rd \n| office           = Mayor of Quebec City\n| predecessor      = [[Ren\u00e9-\u00c9douard Caron]]\n| successor        = [[Narcisse-Fortunat Belleau]] \n| term_start       = 1846\n| term_end         = 1850\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1807|10|12}}\n| birth_place      = York (Toronto), Upper Canada\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1884|3|5|1807|10|12}}\n| death_place      = Quebec City, Quebec\n| resting_place    = [[Mount Hermon Cemetery]], [[Sillery, Quebec City|Sillery]], Quebec \n| nationality      = \n| spouse           = \n| party            = \n| relations        = [[George Okill Stuart (clergyman)|George Okill Stuart]], father\n| children         = \n| residence        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| religion         = \n}}\n'''George Okill Stuart''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|QC}} (October 12, 1807 &ndash; March 5, 1884) was an Anglo-[[Quebec]] lawyer, judge and political figure.\n\nHe was born in (York, later [[Toronto]]), [[Upper Canada]] in 1807, the son of [[George Okill Stuart]] and was educated at [[Kingston, Ontario|Kingston]] and [[Quebec City]]. He articled in law with his uncle, [[James Stuart (Lower Canada statesman)|James Stuart]], and was admitted to the Lower Canada Bar in 1830. He entered practice with his uncle from 1834 until 1838, when his uncle became chief justice for [[Lower Canada]]. Stuart served as solicitor for the city of Quebec from 1841 to 1843. In 1843, he was elected to city council and he served as mayor from 1846 to 1850. In 1851, he was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of the Province of Canada]] for Quebec City as an independent Conservative. He was defeated in 1854 but reelected in an 1857 by-election. Stuart was b\u00e2tonnier for the bar of Lower Canada from 1851 to 1853. In 1854, he was named [[Queen's Counsel]]. He was an assistant judge in the Superior Court of Lower Canada for a short time in 1855. Stuart served as a director for the Saint Maurice Railway and Navigation Company. He started a law firm with John Murphy around 1861 that operated until 1873. In 1873, he became an assistant to [[Henry Black (Quebec judge)|Henry Black]], a judge in the [[Vice admiralty court|Vice Admiralty Court]] at Quebec; when Black died later that year, Stuart was chosen as his replacement and served in that function until his death at Quebec City in 1884.\n\nStuart also published a volume of case reports from the courts of King's Bench, the provincial Court of Appeals of Lower Canada and the Court of Vice Admiralty and edited another work on cases related to maritime law.\n\n==External links==\n* {{QuebecMNAbio|stuart-george-okill-5421}}\n*{{Cite DCB|5855}}\n*{{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{Mayor of Quebec City}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stuart, George Okill}}\n[[Category:1807 births]]\n[[Category:1884 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Legislative Assembly of the Province of Canada]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Quebec City]]\n[[Category:Judges in Quebec]]\n[[Category:United Empire Loyalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Canadian Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:Burials at Mount Hermon Cemetery]]\n", "name_user": "W.andrea", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove comma before postnominals to fix grammar in article preview", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Okill_Stuart_Jr."}
{"title_page": "Arabic coffee", "text_new": "{{about|methods of preparation of a drink|the species of coffee plant|Coffea arabica}}\n{{short description|A version of brewed Arabian coffee beans}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name = Arabic coffee\n| image = [[Image:A dallah a traditional Arabic coffee pot with cups and coffee beans.jpg||260px]] \n| caption = A [[Dallah (coffee pot)|dallah]] is a traditional Arabic coffee pot with cups and coffee beans\n| alternate_name = Qahwah arabiyya\n| country = [[Yemen]] \n| region =  [[Arab World]], [[Middle East]] \n| national_cuisine = [[Arab cuisine]] \n| year = 15th century\n| mintime = \n| maxtime = \n| type = [[Coffea arabica]]\n| course = [[Drink]]\n| served = [[List of hot drinks|Hot]]\n| main_ingredient = \n| minor_ingredient =\n| variations = \n| serving_size = 100 g\n| calories = \n| protein = \n| fat = \n| carbohydrate = \n| glycemic_index = \n| other = \n}}\n'''Arabic coffee''' refers to a version of the brewed coffee of ''[[Coffea arabica]]'' beans. Arabic coffee is typically grown at a height of 1000 to 2000 meters, and represents about 60-70% of the coffee industry in the world.<ref name=\"ICO\">{{cite web|title=Botanical Aspects |publisher=International Coffee Organization |location=London |url=http://www.ico.org/botanical.asp |accessdate=4 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090324155957/http://www.ico.org/botanical.asp |archivedate=24 March 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1.2.5-World coffee trade-World production by type: arabica and robusta|url=http://www.intracen.org/coffee-guide/world-coffee-trade/world-production-by-type-arabica-and-robusta/|website=www.intracen.org}}</ref> Most [[Arab world|Arab countries]] throughout the [[Middle East]] have developed unique methods for brewing and preparing coffee. [[Cardamom]] is an often-added spice,<ref>{{cite web|title=Ingredients Arabic Coffee|url=http://www.nestle-family.com/nescafe/arabiana/nescafe-arabiana-product.aspx|access-date=2017-10-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228223111/http://www.nestle-family.com/nescafe/arabiana/nescafe-arabiana-product.aspx|archive-date=2018-12-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> but it can alternatively be served plain .\n\nThere are several different styles to brewing the coffee depending on the preference of the drinker. Some methods keep the coffee light, which usually contains cardamom, whereas others can make it dark. Arabic coffee is [[Taste|bitter]], and typically no sugar is added. It is usually served in a small cup that is adorned with a decorative pattern, known as a finj\u0101n. Culturally, Arabic coffee is served during family gatherings or when receiving guests.\n\nArabic coffee is ingrained within Middle Eastern and Arab culture and tradition, and is the most popular form of coffee brewed in the Middle East. It originated in the [[Middle East]], beginning in [[Yemen]] and eventually travelling to [[Mecca]] ([[Hejaz]]), [[Egypt]], the [[Levant]], and then, in the mid-16th century, to [[Turkey]] and from there to Europe where Coffee eventually became popular as well.<ref name=\"Bennett\" /> Arabic coffee is an [[Intangible cultural heritage|Intangible Cultural Heritage]] of [[Arab states]] confirmed by [[UNESCO]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/en/RL/arabic-coffee-a-symbol-of-generosity-01074|title=Arabic coffee, a symbol of generosity - intangible heritage - Culture Sector - UNESCO|website=www.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\n[[File:John Frederick Lewis 004.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Arab women]] (coffee bearer) by [[John Frederick Lewis]] (1857). in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]])]]\nThe word \"coffee\" entered the English language in 1582 via the Dutch ''koffie'',<ref>''[[OED]]'', ''s.v.'' \"Coffee\".</ref> borrowed from the [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] ''kahve'', in turn borrowed from the [[Arabic]] [[wiktionary:\u0642\u0647\u0648\u0629|\u0642\u064e\u0647\u0652\u0648\u064e\u0629]] (qahwa, \u201ccoffee, a brew\u201d).<ref name=OED>''Oxford English Dictionary'', 1st&nbsp;ed. \"coffee, ''n.''\" Oxford University Press (Oxford), 1891.</ref> The word ''qahwah'' may have originally referred to the drink's reputation as an appetite suppressant from the word ''qahiya'' ({{lang-ar|\u0642\u064e\u0647\u0650\u064a\u064e|qahiya|lit=to lack hunger}}).<ref name=\"Kaye1986\">{{cite journal|last=Kaye|first=Alan|date=1986|title=The Etymology of Coffee: The Dark Brew|journal=Journal of the American Oriental Society|volume=106|issue=3|pages=557\u2013558|doi=10.2307/602112|jstor=602112}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|script-title=ar:\u0642\u0647\u064a |url=http://www.baheth.info/all.jsp?term=%D9%82%D9%87%D9%8A|work=\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0627\u062d\u062b \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a |accessdate=September 25, 2011|language=ar}}(see also [http://www.ejtaal.net/aa/#hw4=943,ll=2665,ls=16,la=3767,sg=880,ha=644,br=804,pr=130,aan=541,mgf=739,vi=311,kz=2231,mr=568,mn=1168,uqw=1367,umr=905,ums=767,umj=690,ulq=1452,uqa=359,uqq=319,bdw=h739,amr=h534,asb=h825,auh=h1333,dhq=h469,mht=h766,msb=h205,tla=h88,amj=h681,ens=h1,mis=h1 qahiya: Hans Wehr's ''Dictionary of Modern Written Arabic'']. page 930.)</ref>  The name ''qahwah'' is not used for the berry or plant (the products of the region), which are known in Arabic as ''bunn''.  Semitic had a root ''qhh'' \"dark color\", which became a natural designation for the beverage.  According to this analysis, the feminine form ''qahwah'' (also meaning \"dark in color, dull(ing), dry, sour\") also had the meaning of wine, which was also often dark in color.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Alan S. |last=Kaye |title=The etymology of \"coffee\": The dark brew |journal=Journal of the American Oriental Society |volume=106 |number=3 |pages=557\u2013558 |year=1986 |doi=10.2307/602112 |jstor=602112}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe earliest credible evidence of either coffee drinking or knowledge of the coffee tree appears in the middle of the 15th century, in [[Yemen]]'s [[Sufi]] monasteries.<ref name=\"Bennett\">{{cite book|first1=Bennett Alan|last1=Weinberg|first2=Bonnie K.|last2=Bealer|title=The world of caffeine|year=2001|pages=[https://archive.org/details/worldofcaffeines00benn/page/n380 3]\u20134|url=https://archive.org/details/worldofcaffeines00benn |url-access=registration|quote=coffee goat ethiopia Kaldi.| isbn=978-0-415-92723-9 | publisher=Routledge}}</ref> Sufis used it to keep themselves alert during their nighttime devotions. A translation of Al-Jaziri's manuscript<ref name=\":5\">Al-Jaziri's manuscript work is of considerable interest with regards to the history of coffee in Europe as well. A copy reached the French royal library, where it was translated in part by [[Antoine Galland]] as ''De l'origine et du progr\u00e8s du caf\u00e9''.</ref> traces the spread of coffee from ''Arabia Felix'' (the present day Yemen) northward to [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]], and then to the larger cities of [[Cairo]], [[Damascus]], [[Baghdad]], and [[Constantinople]]. In 1511, it was forbidden for its stimulating effect by conservative, orthodox imams at a theological court in [[Mecca]].<ref>{{cite web|title=resource for Arabic books|url=http://www.alwaraq.net/Core/waraq/bibliography_indetail?id=184|website=www.alwaraq.net}}</ref> However, these bans were to be overturned in 1524 by an order of the [[Ottoman Dynasty|Ottoman Turkish]] [[Sultan]] [[Suleiman the Magnificent|Suleiman I]], with [[Grand Mufti]] [[Mehmet Ebussuud el-\u0130madi]] issuing a ''[[fatwa]]'' allowing the consumption of coffee.<ref>{{cite book | last= Schneider | first= Irene | chapter= Ebussuud |editor= Michael Stolleis |title= Juristen: ein biographisches Lexikon; von der Antike bis zum 20. Jahrhundert |edition= 2nd |year= 2001 |publisher= Beck |location= M\u00fcnchen |language= German |isbn= 3-406-45957-9 |page= 193}}</ref> In [[Cairo]], Egypt, a similar ban was instituted in 1532, and the coffeehouses and warehouses containing coffee beans were sacked.<ref>{{cite book |author=J. E. Hanauer | title= Folk-lore of the Holy Land |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/FolkLoreOfTheHolyLand | year= 1907 |chapter=About Coffee | quote=[All] the coffee-houses [were] closed, and their keepers pelted with the sherds of their pots and cups. This was in 1524, but by an order of Sel\u00ecm I., the decrees of the learned were reversed, the disturbances in Egypt quieted, the drinking of coffee declared perfectly orthodox |at=pp.&nbsp;291&nbsp;f.}}</ref>\n\n== Preparation ==\n[[Image:Dallahs.png|thumb|220px|[[Dallah (coffee pot)|Dallahs]]]]\nArabic coffee is made from coffee beans roasted very lightly or heavily from {{convert|165|to|210|C|F}} and cardamom, and is a traditional beverage in Arab culture.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.yourmiddleeast.com/features/what-makes-arabic-coffee-unique_9351|title=What makes Arabic coffee unique?|work=Your Middle East|access-date=2017-04-14|language=sv}}</ref> Traditionally, it is roasted on the premises (at home or for special occasions), ground, brewed and served in front of guests. It is often served with dates, dried fruit, candied fruit or nuts.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dlc.fi/~marianna/gourmet/19_30.htm|title=Gulf Arabic coffee - qahwa arabiyyah|website=www.dlc.fi|access-date=2017-04-14}}</ref> Arabic coffee is defined by the method of preparation and flavors, rather than the type of roast beans. Arabic coffee is boiled coffee that is not filtered, made black. Sugar is not typically added, but if so, it can be added during preparation or when serving. It is served in a small delicate cup without handles, called finj\u0101n. Sometimes, the coffee is moved to a larger and more beautiful pour pitcher to serve in front of the guests, called Della. Often, though, the host prepares coffee in the kitchen and highlights a tray of small cups of coffee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.terracerestaurantandlounge.com/how-to-make-arabic-coffee-7-steps/|title=How To Make Arabic Coffee|date=2015-03-01|work=Terrace Restaurant & Lounge|access-date=2017-04-14|language=en-US}}</ref> Unlike its [[Turkish coffee|Turkish]] counterparts, traditional Arabic coffee, with its roots in [[Bedouin]] tradition, is usually unsweetened (qahwah saada), but sugar can be added depending on the preference of drinker. However, this coffee is never sweet syrup, but rather strong and bitter. To make up for the bitter flavor, coffee is usually served with something sweet{{snd}}dates are a traditional accompaniment{{snd}}and other desserts are often served along with a tray of coffee cups.<ref name=\":4\" />[[Image:Coffee Souq Waqif Doha.jpg|thumb|left|widthpx|Kanaka also called rikwah or jezwah at [[Souq Waqif]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]].]]\n\n=== Arabian Peninsula ===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Arabian Peninsula Arabic Coffee.png|thumb|220px|Arabian Peninsula [[Hejazi]]/Najdi Arabic Coffee]] -->\nArabs in the [[Persian Gulf]] are also creative in the way they prepare coffee. Coffee is different from that in Egypt and [[Levant]] in terms of bitterness and the type of cups the coffee is served in. This brewing method is common in [[Najd]] and [[Hejaz]], and sometimes other [[spice]]s like [[saffron]] (to give it a golden color), [[cloves]], and [[cinnamon]]. Arabic coffee in [[Najd]] and [[Hejaz]] takes a golden color while in [[Arabian Peninsula|North Arabia]] a type of Arabic coffee known as qahwah sham\u0101lia<ref>{{cite web |last1=Al Asfour |first1=Saud |title=\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0647\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a\u064a\u0629.. \u0623\u0635\u0627\u0644\u0629 \u0648\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u0629 |url=https://alqabas.com/540745/ |website=Alqabas}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Al Asfour |first1=Saud |title=\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0647\u0648\u062c\u064a.. \"\u0635\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0651\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0647\u0648\u0629\" \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0642\u062f\u064a\u0645\u0627\u064b |url=https://alqabas.com/251362/ |website=Alqabas}}</ref>  (literally means Northern Coffee) it looks darker in color, because brewing the Northern coffee takes a bit longer. Northern coffee is also known as [[Bedouin]] coffee in [[Jordan]]. Some people add a little-[[evaporated milk]] to slightly alter its color; however, this is rare. It is prepared in and served from a special coffee pot called [[Dallah (coffee pot)|dallah]] ({{lang-ar|'''\u062f\u0644\u0629'''}}); more commonly used is the coffee pot called [[cezve]] (also called rikwah or kanaka) and the coffee cups are small with no handle called ''fenjan''. The portions are small, covering just the bottom of the cup. It is served in homes, and in good restaurants by specially clad waiters called ''gahwaji'', and it is almost always accompanied with dates. It is always offered with the compliments of the house.[[Image:Different_Types_of_Arabic_Coffee.jpg|thumb|367x367px|The different types of Arabic coffee with the [[Hejazi]] / [[Najd]]i golden coffee seen on the left and the [[Levant]]ine black \"qahwah s\u0101dah\" (plain coffee) on the right.]]\n\n=== Levant ===\nThe hot beverage that [[Palestinians]] consume is coffee{{snd}}served in the morning and throughout the day. The coffee of choice is usually Arabic coffee. Arabic coffee is similar to Turkish coffee, but the former is spiced with [[cardamom]] and is usually unsweetened.<ref name=\"IMEU1\">[http://imeu.net/news/article001840.shtml The rich flavors of Palestine] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416133124/http://imeu.net/news/article001840.shtml |date=2009-04-16 }} Farsakh, Mai M. Institute for Middle East Understanding (IMEU), (Originally published by [http://www.thisweekinpalestine.com/ This Week in Palestine]) 2006-06-21 Accessed on 2007-12-18</ref> Among [[Bedouin]]s and most other [[Arab]]s throughout the region of Palestine, bitter coffee, known as ''qahwah sadah'' (Lit. plain coffee), was a symbol of [[hospitality]]. Pouring the drink was ceremonial; it would involve the host or his eldest son moving clockwise among guests{{snd}}who were judged by age and status{{snd}}pouring coffee into tiny cups from a brass pot. It was considered \"polite\" for guests to accept only three cups of coffee and then end their last cup by saying ''daymen'', meaning \"always\", but intending to mean \"may you always have the means to serve coffee\".<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/gp/reader/0931722934/ref=sib_dp_pt#reader-link A Taste of Palestine: Menus and Memories] (1993). [[Aziz Shihab]]. Corona Publishing Co. p.5 {{ISBN|978-0-931722-93-6}}</ref>\n[[File:Bedouincoffeecup.jpg|thumb|left|[[Arabs|Arab]] [[Bedouin]] from a beehive village in [[Aleppo]], [[State of Syria|Syria]], sipping the traditional murra (bitter) coffee, 1930]]\nIn Lebanon, the coffee is prepared in a long-handled [[Coffeemaker|coffee pot]] called \"rakwe\". Coffee is poured directly from \"rakwe\" to a small cup that is adorned with a decorative pattern, known as a finj\u0101n.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://food-heritage.org/wordpress/lebanese-coffee/|title=Food Heritage Foundation \u2013 Lebanese coffee|website=food-heritage.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-20}}</ref> The finj\u0101n has a capacity of 60-90 ml (2-3 oz fl). Lebanese coffee is traditionally strong and black and is similar to the coffee of other Middle Eastern countries. However it differs in its beans and roast, where the blonde and dark beans are mixed together. It is also ground into a very particle like size.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://maatouk.com/lebCoffee.aspx|title=Lebanese Coffee, Coffee passion|website=maatouk.com|access-date=2018-08-20}}</ref> It is often joked that a Lebanese person who does not drink coffee is in danger of losing their nationality.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nDrinks in [[Syria]] vary depending on the time of day and the occasion. Arabic coffee is the most well-known hot drink usually prepared in the morning at [[breakfast]] or in the evening. It is usually served for guests or after [[food]].\n\nArabic coffee is much more than just a drink in Jordan{{snd}}it is a traditional sign of respect and a way to bring people together. Black, cardamom-flavored Arabic coffee, also known as ''qahwah s\u0101dah'' (welcome coffee), deeply ingrained in [[Culture of Jordan|Jordanian culture]]. Providing coffee (and tea) to guests is a large part of the intimate hospitality of the [[Jordan|Hashemite Kingdom]].\n\n=== Morocco ===\nWhile the national drink of Morocco is [[Maghrebi mint tea|gunpowder green tea brewed with fresh mint]] and espresso is very popular, Arabic coffee is also widely consumed, especially on formal occasions. It is often made with the purpose of conducting a business deal and welcoming someone into one's home for the first time, and frequently served at weddings and on important occasions.\n\n== Cultivation ==\n[[File:Jerusalem cafe du rue 1858.jpg|thumb|upright|A ''maqhah'' in [[Jerusalem]] during [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], 1858]]\nMuch of the popularization of coffee is due to its cultivation in the Arab world, beginning in what is now Yemen, by Sufi monks in the 15th century.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Cuisine and Culture: A History of Food and People|last=Civitello|first=Linda|publisher=John Wiley|year=2007|isbn=9780471741725|location=Hoboken, NJ|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref> Through thousands of Arabs pilgrimaging to [[Mecca]], the enjoyment and harvesting of coffee, or the \"wine of Araby\" spread to other Arab countries (e.g. Egypt, [[Syria]]) and eventually to a majority of the world through the 16th century. Coffee, in addition to being essential in the home, became a major part of social life.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Alif Baa: Introduction to Arabic Letters and Sounds|last=Brustad|first=Kristen|last2=Al-Batal|first2=Mahmoud|last3=Al-Tonsi|first3=Abbas|publisher=Georgetown University Press|year=2010|isbn=9781589016330|location=|page=132|quote=|via=}}</ref> Coffeehouses, qahwa \u0642\u064e\u0647\u0648\u0629 in [[Modern Standard Arabic]], became \"Schools of the Wise\" as they developed into places of intellectual discussion, in addition to centers of relaxation and comradery.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncausa.org/About-Coffee/History-of-Coffee|title=The History Of Coffee|last=|first=|date=October 24, 2016|website=ncausa.org|publisher=National Coffee Association of the U.S.A.|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Coffeehouse ==\n[[Image:1004-CoffeeSceneCairo18th.jpg|thumb|left|Coffeehouse in Cairo, 18th c.]]\n[[Coffeehouse]] culture began in the [[Arab world]], and eventually spread to other areas of the world and blended with the local culture.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Coffee and Coffeehouses The Origins of a Social Beverage in the Medieval Near East.|last=S.|first=Hattox, Ralph|date=2014-01-01|publisher=University of Washington Press|isbn=978-0295805498|oclc=934667227}}</ref> Traditional Arab coffeehouses are places where mostly men meet to socialize over games, coffee, and water pipes ([[Hookah|shisha]] or argille). Depending on where the coffeehouse is, its specialty differs. In [[Maghreb]], green tea is served with mint or coffee is served Arab and/or European style. Arabic coffee, or Turkish coffee, is made in [[Egypt]] and the [[Levant|Levant countries]]. Arabic coffee is a very small amount of dark coffee boiled in a pot and presented in a demitasse cup. Particularly in Egypt, coffee is served mazbuuta, which means the amount of sugar will be \"just right\", about one teaspoon per cup. However, in the [[Arabian Peninsula]], Arabic coffee is roasted in such a way that the coffee is almost clear. In all of the Arab world, it is traditional for the host to refill the guest's cup until politely signaled that the guest is finished.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Served ==\n[[File:A man pours Arabic coffee.ogg|thumb|An Arab man pours the traditional cup of Arabic coffee in Levant]]\nArabic coffee is usually served just a few [[Litre|centiliters]] at a time. The waiter/host serves the guest just enough to cover the bottom of the cup. Usually, the coffee is boiling hot, so larger amounts would take too long to cool to a drinkable temperature.<ref name=\":1\" /> The guest drinks it and if he wishes, he will gesture to the waiter not to pour any more. Otherwise, the host/waiter will continue to serve another few centilitres at a time until the guest indicates he has had enough. The most common practice is to drink only one cup since serving coffee serves as a ceremonial act of kindness and hospitality. Sometimes people also drink larger volumes during conversations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gwnunn.com/blog/2011/03/arabic-coffee-service/|title=Arabic Coffee Service {{!}} GWNunn.com|website=gwnunn.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Customs ==\nThe cups are normally only filled partway, and the custom is to drink three cups.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://cabincrewexcellence.com/arabic-coffee-a-welcoming-ritual/|title=Arabic Coffee - A Welcoming Ritual|work=Cabin Crew Excellence|access-date=2017-04-14|language=en-US}}</ref> Arabic coffee has a prominent place in traditional [[Arabs|Arab]] holidays and special events such as [[Ramadan]] and [[Muslim holidays|Eid]].\n\n=== Fortune-telling ===\nArabic coffee reading ({{Lang-ar|\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0621\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0646\u062c\u0627\u0646|qir\u0101\u02beat al-finj\u0101n|}}), is similar to tea-leaf reading; the client is asked to consume strong fresh Arabic coffee leaving approximately a teaspoon of liquid in the cup. The cup is then inverted onto a saucer to allowing the residual liquid to drain away. The reader will then interpret the patterns formed by the thick residue on the inside of the cup.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane - Fortune Teller {{!}} Middlesex{{!}} South East{{!}} UK - Contraband Events|url=https://www.contrabandevents.com/project/jane-fortune-teller-middlesex-south-east-uk/|website=Contraband Events}}</ref>\n\n=== Funeral ===\nArabic [[funeral]]s gather families and extended relatives, who drink bitter and unsweetened coffee and restore the life and characteristics of the deceased. The men and women gather separately, and it has become very fashionable to employ very presentable women whose only job is to serve coffee all day to the women. Male waiters serve the men. [[Arab Muslims]] and [[Arab Christians|Christians]] share this tradition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://imeu.org/article/social-customs-and-traditions|title=Palestinian Social Customs and Traditions {{!}} IMEU|last=IMEU|website=imeu.org|language=en|access-date=2017-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Nutrition facts ==\nA small cup of Arabic coffee has almost no calories or fat. It contains a small amount of protein.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.livestrong.com/article/296924-arabic-coffee-nutrition-information/|title=Arabic Coffee Nutrition Information|last=Cherney|first=Kristeen|work=LIVESTRONG.COM|access-date=2017-04-14|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=http://blog.raynatours.com/5-interesting-facts-arabic-coffee/|title=5 Interesting Facts About Arabic Coffee|last=Tulsani|first=Manoj|date=2013-05-29|work=Travel Tips and Experience - Rayna Tours and Travels|access-date=2017-04-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Arabic tea]]\n*[[Arab cuisine]]\n*[[Home roasting coffee]]\n*[[Green coffee]]\n*[[Turkish coffee]]\n*[https://www.emiraticoffee.com/ Emirati Coffee Co]\n{{portal bar|Coffee}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-7wnpIi3VRwC&pg=PA37 | title=Middle Eastern Kitchen | publisher=Hippocrene Books | author=Basan, Ghillie | year=2007 | page=37 | isbn=978-0781811903}}\n* {{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0QxRp3jlQlsC&pg=PA44 | title=Coffee Love: 50 Ways to Drink Your Java | publisher=John Wiley & Sons | author=Young, Daniel | year=2009 | page=44 | isbn=978-0470289372}}\n{{Coffee|nocat=1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arabic Coffee}}\n[[Category:Arabic drinks]]\n[[Category:Arab culture]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Yemeni cuisine]]\n[[Category:Omani cuisine]]\n[[Category:Levantine cuisine]]\n[[Category:Palestinian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Lebanese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Syrian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Jordanian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Iraqi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Qatari cuisine]]\n[[Category:Coffee preparation]]\n[[Category:Arab inventions]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|methods of preparation of a drink|the species of coffee plant|Coffea arabica}}\n{{short description|A version of brewed Arabian coffee beans}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name = Arabic coffee\n| image = [[Image:A dallah a traditional Arabic coffee pot with cups and coffee beans.jpg||260px]] \n| caption = A [[Dallah (coffee pot)|dallah]] is a traditional Arabic coffee pot with cups and coffee beans\n| alternate_name = Qahwah arabiyya\n| country = [[Yemen]] \n| region =  [[Arab World]], [[Middle East]] \n| national_cuisine = [[Arab cuisine]] \n| year = 15th century\n| mintime = \n| maxtime = \n| type = [[Coffea arabica]]\n| course = [[Drink]]\n| served = [[List of hot drinks|Hot]]\n| main_ingredient = \n| minor_ingredient =\n| variations = \n| serving_size = 100 g\n| calories = \n| protein = \n| fat = \n| carbohydrate = \n| glycemic_index = \n| other = \n}}\n'''Arabic coffee''' refers to a version of the brewed coffee of ''[[Coffea arabica]]'' beans. Arabic coffee is typically grown at a height of 1000 to 2000 meters, and represents about 60-70% of the coffee industry in the world.<ref name=\"ICO\">{{cite web|title=Botanical Aspects |publisher=International Coffee Organization |location=London |url=http://www.ico.org/botanical.asp |accessdate=4 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090324155957/http://www.ico.org/botanical.asp |archivedate=24 March 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1.2.5-World coffee trade-World production by type: arabica and robusta|url=http://www.intracen.org/coffee-guide/world-coffee-trade/world-production-by-type-arabica-and-robusta/|website=www.intracen.org}}</ref> Most [[Arab world|Arab countries]] throughout the [[Middle East]] have developed unique methods for brewing and preparing coffee. [[Cardamom]] is an often-added spice,<ref>{{cite web|title=Ingredients Arabic Coffee|url=http://www.nestle-family.com/nescafe/arabiana/nescafe-arabiana-product.aspx|access-date=2017-10-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228223111/http://www.nestle-family.com/nescafe/arabiana/nescafe-arabiana-product.aspx|archive-date=2018-12-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> but it can alternatively be served plain .\n\nThere are several different styles to brewing the coffee depending on the preference of the drinker. Some methods keep the coffee light, which usually contains cardamom, whereas others can make it dark. Arabic coffee is [[Taste|bitter]], and typically no sugar is added. It is usually served in a small cup that is adorned with a decorative pattern, known as a finj\u0101n. Culturally, Arabic coffee is served during family gatherings or when receiving guests.\n\nArabic coffee is ingrained within Middle Eastern and Arab culture and tradition, and is the most popular form of coffee brewed in the Middle East. It originated in the [[Middle East]], beginning in [[Yemen]] and eventually travelling to [[Mecca]] ([[Hejaz]]), [[Egypt]], the [[Levant]], and then, in the mid-16th century, to [[Turkey]] and from there to Europe where Coffee eventually became popular as well.<ref name=\"Bennett\" /> Arabic coffee is an [[Intangible cultural heritage|Intangible Cultural Heritage]] of [[Arab states]] confirmed by [[UNESCO]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/en/RL/arabic-coffee-a-symbol-of-generosity-01074|title=Arabic coffee, a symbol of generosity - intangible heritage - Culture Sector - UNESCO|website=www.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== Etymology ==\n[[File:John Frederick Lewis 004.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Arab women]] (coffee bearer) by [[John Frederick Lewis]] (1857). in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]])]]\nThe word \"coffee\" entered the English language in 1582 via the Dutch ''koffie'',<ref>''[[OED]]'', ''s.v.'' \"Coffee\".</ref> borrowed from the [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] ''kahve'', in turn borrowed from the [[Arabic]] [[wiktionary:\u0642\u0647\u0648\u0629|\u0642\u064e\u0647\u0652\u0648\u064e\u0629]] (qahwa, \u201ccoffee, a brew\u201d).<ref name=OED>''Oxford English Dictionary'', 1st&nbsp;ed. \"coffee, ''n.''\" Oxford University Press (Oxford), 1891.</ref> The word ''qahwah'' may have originally referred to the drink's reputation as an appetite suppressant from the word ''qahiya'' ({{lang-ar|\u0642\u064e\u0647\u0650\u064a\u064e|qahiya|lit=to lack hunger}}).<ref name=\"Kaye1986\">{{cite journal|last=Kaye|first=Alan|date=1986|title=The Etymology of Coffee: The Dark Brew|journal=Journal of the American Oriental Society|volume=106|issue=3|pages=557\u2013558|doi=10.2307/602112|jstor=602112}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|script-title=ar:\u0642\u0647\u064a |url=http://www.baheth.info/all.jsp?term=%D9%82%D9%87%D9%8A|work=\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0627\u062d\u062b \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a |accessdate=September 25, 2011|language=ar}}(see also [http://www.ejtaal.net/aa/#hw4=943,ll=2665,ls=16,la=3767,sg=880,ha=644,br=804,pr=130,aan=541,mgf=739,vi=311,kz=2231,mr=568,mn=1168,uqw=1367,umr=905,ums=767,umj=690,ulq=1452,uqa=359,uqq=319,bdw=h739,amr=h534,asb=h825,auh=h1333,dhq=h469,mht=h766,msb=h205,tla=h88,amj=h681,ens=h1,mis=h1 qahiya: Hans Wehr's ''Dictionary of Modern Written Arabic'']. page 930.)</ref>  The name ''qahwah'' is not used for the berry or plant (the products of the region), which are known in Arabic as ''bunn''.  Semitic had a root ''qhh'' \"dark color\", which became a natural designation for the beverage.  According to this analysis, the feminine form ''qahwah'' (also meaning \"dark in color, dull(ing), dry, sour\") also had the meaning of wine, which was also often dark in color.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Alan S. |last=Kaye |title=The etymology of \"coffee\": The dark brew |journal=Journal of the American Oriental Society |volume=106 |number=3 |pages=557\u2013558 |year=1986 |doi=10.2307/602112 |jstor=602112}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe earliest credible evidence of either coffee drinking or knowledge of the coffee tree appears in the middle of the 15th century, in [[Yemen]]'s [[Sufi]] monasteries.<ref name=\"Bennett\">{{cite book|first1=Bennett Alan|last1=Weinberg|first2=Bonnie K.|last2=Bealer|title=The world of caffeine|year=2001|pages=[https://archive.org/details/worldofcaffeines00benn/page/n380 3]\u20134|url=https://archive.org/details/worldofcaffeines00benn |url-access=registration|quote=coffee goat ethiopia Kaldi.| isbn=978-0-415-92723-9 | publisher=Routledge}}</ref> Sufis used it to keep themselves alert during their nighttime devotions. A translation of Al-Jaziri's manuscript<ref name=\":5\">Al-Jaziri's manuscript work is of considerable interest with regards to the history of coffee in Europe as well. A copy reached the French royal library, where it was translated in part by [[Antoine Galland]] as ''De l'origine et du progr\u00e8s du caf\u00e9''.</ref> traces the spread of coffee from ''Arabia Felix'' (the present day Yemen) northward to [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]], and then to the larger cities of [[Cairo]], [[Damascus]], [[Baghdad]], and [[Constantinople]]. In 1511, it was forbidden for its stimulating effect by conservative, orthodox imams at a theological court in [[Mecca]].<ref>{{cite web|title=resource for Arabic books|url=http://www.alwaraq.net/Core/waraq/bibliography_indetail?id=184|website=www.alwaraq.net}}</ref> However, these bans were to be overturned in 1524 by an order of the [[Ottoman Dynasty|Ottoman Turkish]] [[Sultan]] [[Suleiman the Magnificent|Suleiman I]], with [[Grand Mufti]] [[Mehmet Ebussuud el-\u0130madi]] issuing a ''[[fatwa]]'' allowing the consumption of coffee.<ref>{{cite book | last= Schneider | first= Irene | chapter= Ebussuud |editor= Michael Stolleis |title= Juristen: ein biographisches Lexikon; von der Antike bis zum 20. Jahrhundert |edition= 2nd |year= 2001 |publisher= Beck |location= M\u00fcnchen |language= German |isbn= 3-406-45957-9 |page= 193}}</ref> In [[Cairo]], Egypt, a similar ban was instituted in 1532, and the coffeehouses and warehouses containing coffee beans were sacked.<ref>{{cite book |author=J. E. Hanauer | title= Folk-lore of the Holy Land |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/FolkLoreOfTheHolyLand | year= 1907 |chapter=About Coffee | quote=[All] the coffee-houses [were] closed, and their keepers pelted with the sherds of their pots and cups. This was in 1524, but by an order of Sel\u00ecm I., the decrees of the learned were reversed, the disturbances in Egypt quieted, the drinking of coffee declared perfectly orthodox |at=pp.&nbsp;291&nbsp;f.}}</ref>\n\n== Preparation ==\n[[Image:Dallahs.png|thumb|220px|[[Dallah (coffee pot)|Dallahs]]]]\nArabic coffee is made from coffee beans roasted very lightly or heavily from {{convert|165|to|210|C|F}} and cardamom, and is a traditional beverage in Arab culture.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.yourmiddleeast.com/features/what-makes-arabic-coffee-unique_9351|title=What makes Arabic coffee unique?|work=Your Middle East|access-date=2017-04-14|language=sv}}</ref> Traditionally, it is roasted on the premises (at home or for special occasions), ground, brewed and served in front of guests. It is often served with dates, dried fruit, candied fruit or nuts.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dlc.fi/~marianna/gourmet/19_30.htm|title=Gulf Arabic coffee - qahwa arabiyyah|website=www.dlc.fi|access-date=2017-04-14}}</ref> Arabic coffee is defined by the method of preparation and flavors, rather than the type of roast beans. Arabic coffee is boiled coffee that is not filtered, made black. Sugar is not typically added, but if so, it can be added during preparation or when serving. It is served in a small delicate cup without handles, called finj\u0101n. Sometimes, the coffee is moved to a larger and more beautiful pour pitcher to serve in front of the guests, called Della. Often, though, the host prepares coffee in the kitchen and highlights a tray of small cups of coffee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.terracerestaurantandlounge.com/how-to-make-arabic-coffee-7-steps/|title=How To Make Arabic Coffee|date=2015-03-01|work=Terrace Restaurant & Lounge|access-date=2017-04-14|language=en-US}}</ref> Unlike its [[Turkish coffee|Turkish]] counterparts, traditional Arabic coffee, with its roots in [[Bedouin]] tradition, is usually unsweetened (qahwah saada), but sugar can be added depending on the preference of drinker. However, this coffee is never sweet syrup, but rather strong and bitter. To make up for the bitter flavor, coffee is usually served with something sweet{{snd}}dates are a traditional accompaniment{{snd}}and other desserts are often served along with a tray of coffee cups.<ref name=\":4\" />[[Image:Coffee Souq Waqif Doha.jpg|thumb|left|widthpx|Kanaka also called rikwah or jezwah at [[Souq Waqif]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]].]]\n\n=== Arabian Peninsula ===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Arabian Peninsula Arabic Coffee.png|thumb|220px|Arabian Peninsula [[Hejazi]]/Najdi Arabic Coffee]] -->\nArabs in the [[Persian Gulf]] are also creative in the way they prepare coffee. Coffee is different from that in Egypt and [[Levant]] in terms of bitterness and the type of cups the coffee is served in. This brewing method is common in [[Najd]] and [[Hejaz]], and sometimes other [[spice]]s like [[saffron]] (to give it a golden color), [[cloves]], and [[cinnamon]]. Arabic coffee in [[Najd]] and [[Hejaz]] takes a golden color while in [[Arabian Peninsula|North Arabia]] a type of Arabic coffee known as qahwah sham\u0101lia<ref>{{cite web |last1=Al Asfour |first1=Saud |title=\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0647\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a\u064a\u0629.. \u0623\u0635\u0627\u0644\u0629 \u0648\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642\u0629 |url=https://alqabas.com/540745/ |website=Alqabas}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Al Asfour |first1=Saud |title=\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0647\u0648\u062c\u064a.. \"\u0635\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0651\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0647\u0648\u0629\" \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0642\u062f\u064a\u0645\u0627\u064b |url=https://alqabas.com/251362/ |website=Alqabas}}</ref>  (literally means Northern Coffee) it looks darker in color, because brewing the Northern coffee takes a bit longer. Northern coffee is also known as [[Bedouin]] coffee in [[Jordan]]. Some people add a little-[[evaporated milk]] to slightly alter its color; however, this is rare. It is prepared in and served from a special coffee pot called [[Dallah (coffee pot)|dallah]] ({{lang-ar|'''\u062f\u0644\u0629'''}}); more commonly used is the coffee pot called [[cezve]] (also called rikwah or kanaka) and the coffee cups are small with no handle called ''fenjan''. The portions are small, covering just the bottom of the cup. It is served in homes, and in good restaurants by specially clad waiters called ''gahwaji'', and it is almost always accompanied with dates. It is always offered with the compliments of the house.[[Image:Different_Types_of_Arabic_Coffee.jpg|thumb|367x367px|The different types of Arabic coffee with the [[Hejazi]] / [[Najd]]i golden coffee seen on the left and the [[Levant]]ine black \"qahwah s\u0101dah\" (plain coffee) on the right.]]\n\n=== Levant ===\nThe hot beverage that [[Palestinians]] consume is coffee{{snd}}served in the morning and throughout the day. The coffee of choice is usually Arabic coffee. Arabic coffee is similar to Turkish coffee, but the former is spiced with [[cardamom]] and is usually unsweetened.<ref name=\"IMEU1\">[http://imeu.net/news/article001840.shtml The rich flavors of Palestine] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416133124/http://imeu.net/news/article001840.shtml |date=2009-04-16 }} Farsakh, Mai M. Institute for Middle East Understanding (IMEU), (Originally published by [http://www.thisweekinpalestine.com/ This Week in Palestine]) 2006-06-21 Accessed on 2007-12-18</ref> Among [[Bedouin]]s and most other [[Arab]]s throughout the region of Palestine, bitter coffee, known as ''qahwah sadah'' (Lit. plain coffee), was a symbol of [[hospitality]]. Pouring the drink was ceremonial; it would involve the host or his eldest son moving clockwise among guests{{snd}}who were judged by age and status{{snd}}pouring coffee into tiny cups from a brass pot. It was considered \"polite\" for guests to accept only three cups of coffee and then end their last cup by saying ''daymen'', meaning \"always\", but intending to mean \"may you always have the means to serve coffee\".<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/gp/reader/0931722934/ref=sib_dp_pt#reader-link A Taste of Palestine: Menus and Memories] (1993). [[Aziz Shihab]]. Corona Publishing Co. p.5 {{ISBN|978-0-931722-93-6}}</ref>\n[[File:Bedouincoffeecup.jpg|thumb|left|[[Arabs|Arab]] [[Bedouin]] from a beehive village in [[Aleppo]], [[State of Syria|Syria]], sipping the traditional murra (bitter) coffee, 1930]]\nIn Lebanon, the coffee is prepared in a long-handled [[Coffeemaker|coffee pot]] called \"rakwe\". Coffee is poured directly from \"rakwe\" to a small cup that is adorned with a decorative pattern, known as a finj\u0101n.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://food-heritage.org/wordpress/lebanese-coffee/|title=Food Heritage Foundation \u2013 Lebanese coffee|website=food-heritage.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-20}}</ref> The finj\u0101n has a capacity of 60-90 ml (2-3 oz fl). Lebanese coffee is traditionally strong and black and is similar to the coffee of other Middle Eastern countries. However it differs in its beans and roast, where the blonde and dark beans are mixed together. It is also ground into a very particle like size.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://maatouk.com/lebCoffee.aspx|title=Lebanese Coffee, Coffee passion|website=maatouk.com|access-date=2018-08-20}}</ref> It is often joked that a Lebanese person who does not drink coffee is in danger of losing their nationality.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nDrinks in [[Syria]] vary depending on the time of day and the occasion. Arabic coffee is the most well-known hot drink usually prepared in the morning at [[breakfast]] or in the evening. It is usually served for guests or after [[food]].\n\nArabic coffee is much more than just a drink in Jordan{{snd}}it is a traditional sign of respect and a way to bring people together. Black, cardamom-flavored Arabic coffee, also known as ''qahwah s\u0101dah'' (welcome coffee), deeply ingrained in [[Culture of Jordan|Jordanian culture]]. Providing coffee (and tea) to guests is a large part of the intimate hospitality of the [[Jordan|Hashemite Kingdom]].\n\n=== Morocco ===\nWhile the national drink of Morocco is [[Maghrebi mint tea|gunpowder green tea brewed with fresh mint]] and espresso is very popular, Arabic coffee is also widely consumed, especially on formal occasions. It is often made with the purpose of conducting a business deal and welcoming someone into one's home for the first time, and frequently served at weddings and on important occasions.\n\n== Cultivation ==\n[[File:Jerusalem cafe du rue 1858.jpg|thumb|upright|A ''maqhah'' in [[Jerusalem]] during [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], 1858]]\nMuch of the popularization of coffee is due to its cultivation in the Arab world, beginning in what is now Yemen, by Sufi monks in the 15th century.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|title=Cuisine and Culture: A History of Food and People|last=Civitello|first=Linda|publisher=John Wiley|year=2007|isbn=9780471741725|location=Hoboken, NJ|pages=|quote=|via=}}</ref> Through thousands of Arabs pilgrimaging to [[Mecca]], the enjoyment and harvesting of coffee, or the \"wine of Araby\" spread to other Arab countries (e.g. Egypt, [[Syria]]) and eventually to a majority of the world through the 16th century. Coffee, in addition to being essential in the home, became a major part of social life.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|title=Alif Baa: Introduction to Arabic Letters and Sounds|last=Brustad|first=Kristen|last2=Al-Batal|first2=Mahmoud|last3=Al-Tonsi|first3=Abbas|publisher=Georgetown University Press|year=2010|isbn=9781589016330|location=|page=132|quote=|via=}}</ref> Coffeehouses, qahwa \u0642\u064e\u0647\u0648\u0629 in [[Modern Standard Arabic]], became \"Schools of the Wise\" as they developed into places of intellectual discussion, in addition to centers of relaxation and comradery.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncausa.org/About-Coffee/History-of-Coffee|title=The History Of Coffee|last=|first=|date=October 24, 2016|website=ncausa.org|publisher=National Coffee Association of the U.S.A.|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Coffeehouse ==\n[[Image:1004-CoffeeSceneCairo18th.jpg|thumb|left|Coffeehouse in Cairo, 18th c.]]\n[[Coffeehouse]] culture began in the [[Arab world]], and eventually spread to other areas of the world and blended with the local culture.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Coffee and Coffeehouses The Origins of a Social Beverage in the Medieval Near East.|last=S.|first=Hattox, Ralph|date=2014-01-01|publisher=University of Washington Press|isbn=978-0295805498|oclc=934667227}}</ref> Traditional Arab coffeehouses are places where mostly men meet to socialize over games, coffee, and water pipes ([[Hookah|shisha]] or argille). Depending on where the coffeehouse is, its specialty differs. In [[Maghreb]], green tea is served with mint or coffee is served Arab and/or European style. Arabic coffee, or Turkish coffee, is made in [[Egypt]] and the [[Levant|Levant countries]]. Arabic coffee is a very small amount of dark coffee boiled in a pot and presented in a demitasse cup. Particularly in Egypt, coffee is served mazbuuta, which means the amount of sugar will be \"just right\", about one teaspoon per cup. However, in the [[Arabian Peninsula]], Arabic coffee is roasted in such a way that the coffee is almost clear. In all of the Arab world, it is traditional for the host to refill the guest's cup until politely signaled that the guest is finished.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Served ==\n[[File:A man pours Arabic coffee.ogg|thumb|An Arab man pours the traditional cup of Arabic coffee in Levant]]\nArabic coffee is usually served just a few [[Litre|centiliters]] at a time. The waiter/host serves the guest just enough to cover the bottom of the cup. Usually, the coffee is boiling hot, so larger amounts would take too long to cool to a drinkable temperature.<ref name=\":1\" /> The guest drinks it and if he wishes, he will gesture to the waiter not to pour any more. Otherwise, the host/waiter will continue to serve another few centilitres at a time until the guest indicates he has had enough. The most common practice is to drink only one cup since serving coffee serves as a ceremonial act of kindness and hospitality. Sometimes people also drink larger volumes during conversations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gwnunn.com/blog/2011/03/arabic-coffee-service/|title=Arabic Coffee Service {{!}} GWNunn.com|website=gwnunn.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Customs ==\nThe cups are normally only filled partway, and the custom is to drink three cups.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://cabincrewexcellence.com/arabic-coffee-a-welcoming-ritual/|title=Arabic Coffee - A Welcoming Ritual|work=Cabin Crew Excellence|access-date=2017-04-14|language=en-US}}</ref> Arabic coffee has a prominent place in traditional [[Arabs|Arab]] holidays and special events such as [[Ramadan]] and [[Muslim holidays|Eid]].\n\n=== Fortune-telling ===\nArabic coffee reading ({{Lang-ar|\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0621\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0646\u062c\u0627\u0646|qir\u0101\u02beat al-finj\u0101n|}}), is similar to tea-leaf reading; the client is asked to consume strong fresh Arabic coffee leaving approximately a teaspoon of liquid in the cup. The cup is then inverted onto a saucer to allowing the residual liquid to drain away. The reader will then interpret the patterns formed by the thick residue on the inside of the cup.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane - Fortune Teller {{!}} Middlesex{{!}} South East{{!}} UK - Contraband Events|url=https://www.contrabandevents.com/project/jane-fortune-teller-middlesex-south-east-uk/|website=Contraband Events}}</ref>\n\n=== Funeral ===\nArabic [[funeral]]s gather families and extended relatives, who drink bitter and unsweetened coffee and restore the life and characteristics of the deceased. The men and women gather separately, and it has become very fashionable to employ very presentable women whose only job is to serve coffee all day to the women. Male waiters serve the men. [[Arab Muslims]] and [[Arab Christians|Christians]] share this tradition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://imeu.org/article/social-customs-and-traditions|title=Palestinian Social Customs and Traditions {{!}} IMEU|last=IMEU|website=imeu.org|language=en|access-date=2017-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Nutrition facts ==\nA small cup of Arabic coffee has almost no calories or fat. It contains a small amount of protein.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.livestrong.com/article/296924-arabic-coffee-nutrition-information/|title=Arabic Coffee Nutrition Information|last=Cherney|first=Kristeen|work=LIVESTRONG.COM|access-date=2017-04-14|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=http://blog.raynatours.com/5-interesting-facts-arabic-coffee/|title=5 Interesting Facts About Arabic Coffee|last=Tulsani|first=Manoj|date=2013-05-29|work=Travel Tips and Experience - Rayna Tours and Travels|access-date=2017-04-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Arabic tea]]\n*[[Arab cuisine]]\n*[[Home roasting coffee]]\n*[[Green coffee]]\n*[[Turkish coffee]]\n{{portal bar|Coffee}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-7wnpIi3VRwC&pg=PA37 | title=Middle Eastern Kitchen | publisher=Hippocrene Books | author=Basan, Ghillie | year=2007 | page=37 | isbn=978-0781811903}}\n* {{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0QxRp3jlQlsC&pg=PA44 | title=Coffee Love: 50 Ways to Drink Your Java | publisher=John Wiley & Sons | author=Young, Daniel | year=2009 | page=44 | isbn=978-0470289372}}\n{{Coffee|nocat=1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arabic Coffee}}\n[[Category:Arabic drinks]]\n[[Category:Arab culture]]\n[[Category:Saudi Arabian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Yemeni cuisine]]\n[[Category:Omani cuisine]]\n[[Category:Levantine cuisine]]\n[[Category:Palestinian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Lebanese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Syrian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Jordanian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Iraqi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Qatari cuisine]]\n[[Category:Coffee preparation]]\n[[Category:Arab inventions]]\n", "name_user": "EmiratiCoffee", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arabic_coffee"}
