0190111041622/http://meteo.hr/klima_e.php?section=klima_podaci&param=k1&Grad=dubrovnik\n| archivedate = 11 January 2019\n| url = http://meteo.hr/klima_e.php?section=klima_podaci&param=k1&Grad=dubrovnik\n| title = Monthly values and extremes: Values for Dubrovnik in 1961\u20132017 period\n| language = Croatian\n| accessdate = 10 January 2019\n| publisher = Croatian Meteorological and Hydrological Service}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{|style=\"width:100%;text-align:center;line-height:1.2em;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\" class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible\"\n|-\n!Colspan=14|Climate data for Dubrovnik\n|-\n!Month\n!Jan\n!Feb\n!Mar\n!Apr\n!May\n!Jun\n!Jul\n!Aug\n!Sep\n!Oct\n!Nov\n!Dec\n!style=\"border-left-width:medium\"|Year\n|-\n!Average sea temperature \u00b0C (\u00b0F)\n|style=\"background:#D3D3FF;color:#000000;\"|14.1<br />(57.4)\n|style=\"background:#D4D4FF;color:#000000;\"|14.2<br />(57.6)\n|style=\"background:#D8D8FF;color:#000000;\"|14.4<br />(57.9)\n|style=\"background:#EAEAFF;color:#000000;\"|15.6<br />(60.1)\n|style=\"background:#FFDD6E;color:#000000;\"|18.7<br />(65.7)\n|style=\"background:#FF8700;color:#000000;\"|23.1<br />(73.6)\n|style=\"background:#FF5800;color:#000000;\"|25.5<br />(77.9)\n|style=\"background:#FF5A00;color:#000000;\"|25.4<br />(77.7)\n|style=\"background:#FF6F00;color:#000000;\"|24.3<br />(75.7)\n|style=\"background:#FFB600;color:#000000;\"|20.7<br />(69.3)\n|style=\"background:#FFE799;color:#000000;\"|18.2<br />(64.8)\n|style=\"background:#EBEBFF;color:#000000;\"|15.7<br />(60.3)\n|style=\"background:#FFD447;color:#000000;border-left-width:medium\"|19.2<br />(66.5)\n|-\n!Mean daily daylight hours\n|style=\"background:#E9E900;color:#000000;\"|9.0\n|style=\"background:#F7F722;color:#000000;\"|11.0\n|style=\"background:#FFFF33;color:#000000;\"|12.0\n|style=\"background:#FFFF44;color:#000000;\"|13.0\n|style=\"background:#FFFF66;color:#000000;\"|15.0\n|style=\"background:#FFFF66;color:#000000;\"|15.0\n|style=\"background:#FFFF66;color:#000000;\"|15.0\n|style=\"background:#FFFF55;color:#000000;\"|14.0\n|style=\"background:#FFFF33;color:#000000;\"|12.0\n|style=\"background:#F7F722;color:#000000;\"|11.0\n|style=\"background:#F0F011;color:#000000;\"|10.0\n|style=\"background:#E9E900;color:#000000;\"|9.0\n|style=\"background:#FFFF35;color:#000000;border-left-width:medium\"|12.2\n|-\n!Average [[Ultraviolet index]]\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;\"|1\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;\"|2\n|style=\"background:#f7e400;color:#000000;\"|4\n|style=\"background:#f7e400;color:#000000;\"|5\n|style=\"background:#f85900;color:#000000;\"|7\n|style=\"background:#d8001d;color:#000000;\"|8\n|style=\"background:#d8001d;color:#000000;\"|9\n|style=\"background:#d8001d;color:#000000;\"|8\n|style=\"background:#f85900;color:#000000;\"|6\n|style=\"background:#f7e400;color:#000000;\"|4\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;\"|2\n|style=\"background:#289500;color:#000000;\"|1\n|style=\"background:#f7e400;color:#000000;border-left-width:medium\"|4.8\n|-\n!Colspan=14 style=\"background:#f8f9fa;font-weight:normal;font-size:95%;\"|Source: Weather Atlas<ref name=\"Weather Atlas\">{{cite web |url=https://www.weather-atlas.com/en/croatia/dubrovnik-climate |title=Dubrovnik, Croatia \u2013 Monthly weather forecast and Climate data |publisher=Weather Atlas |access-date=3 February 2019 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Heritage==\n{{Infobox Historic Site\n|name=Old City of Dubrovnik\n|native_name=Stari grad Dubrovnik\n|native_language=Croatian\n|image=Dubrovnik1.jpg\n|caption=The Old Harbour at Dubrovnik\n|location=[[Dubrovnik-Neretva County]], Croatia\n|area=\n|built=\n|architect=\n|architecture=\n|governing_body=\n|designation1=WHS\n|designation1_offname=\n|designation1_type=Cultural\n|designation1_criteria=i, iii, iv\n|designation1_date = [[List of World Heritage Sites by year of inscription#1979 (3rd session)|1979]] <small>(3rd [[World Heritage Committee|Session]])</small>\n|designation1_number=[https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/95 95]\n|designation1_free1value=[[World Heritage Sites in Europe|Europe and North America]]\n|designation1_free2name=Extension\n|designation1_free2value=1994\n|designation1_free3name=Endangered\n|designation1_free3value=1991\u20131998\n|designation2=Croatia Cultural\n|designation2_offname=Stari grad Dubrovnik\n|designation2_date=\n|designation2_number=\n|designation3=\n|designation3_offname=\n|designation3_date=\n|designation3_number=\n}}\n[[File:Lapad - poluotok.JPG|180px|left|Lapad peninsula]]\n[[File:Banje beach, Dubrovnik, Croatia.JPG|180px|left|Banje beach, Dubrovnik]]\nThe annual [[Dubrovnik Summer Festival]] is a 45-day-long cultural event with live plays, concerts, and games. It has been awarded a Gold International Trophy for Quality (2007) by the Editorial Office in collaboration with the Trade Leaders Club.\n\nThe [[patron saint]] of the city is [[Saint Blaise|Sveti Vlaho (Saint Blaise)]], whose statues are seen around the city. He has an importance similar to that of [[Mark the Evangelist|St. Mark the Evangelist]] to Venice. One of the larger churches in city is named after Saint Blaise.\nFebruary 3 is the feast of [[Saint Blaise|Sveti Vlaho (Saint Blaise)]], who is the city's patron saint. Every year the city of Dubrovnik celebrates the holiday with Mass, parades, and festivities that last for several days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.tzdubrovnik.hr/clanak.shtml?clanak=890 |title=DUBROVNIK news |date=21 October 2007 |work=archive.org |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021141211/http://web.tzdubrovnik.hr/clanak.shtml?clanak=890 |archivedate=2007-10-21 }}</ref>\n\nThe Old Town of Dubrovnik is depicted on the [[Obverse and reverse|reverse]] of the Croatian 50 [[Croatian kuna|kuna]] banknote, issued in 1993 and 2002.<ref name=\"banknotes1993\">{{cite web | url=https://www.hnb.hr/en/currency/banknotes/denominations/50-kuna | title=50 kuna | date=31 January 2015 | work=hnb.hr | publisher=[[Croatian National Bank]] | accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe city boasts many old buildings, such as the [[Trsteno|Arboretum Trsteno]], the oldest [[arboretum]] in the world, which dates back to before 1492. Also, the third-oldest European [[pharmacy]] and the oldest still in operation, having been founded in 1317, is in Dubrovnik, at the Little Brothers monastery.<ref name=dbvonl15>{{cite web|url=http://www.dubrovnik-online.net/english/monuments.php |title=Monuments (1 to 5) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714090903/http://www.dubrovnik-online.com/english/monuments.php |archivedate=2010-07-14 |accessdate=2010-02-16 |publisher=Dubrovnik Online |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn history, many Conversos ([[Marrano]]s) were attracted to Dubrovnik, formerly a considerable seaport. In May 1544, a ship landed there filled exclusively with [[Portugal|Portuguese]] refugees, as Balthasar de Faria reported to King John. Another admirer of Dubrovnik, [[George Bernard Shaw]], visited the city in 1929 and said: \"If you want to see heaven on earth, come to Dubrovnik.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tz-seget.hr/en/40/dubrovnik|title=TZ Seget \u2013 Dubrovnik|author=|date=|work=tz-seget.hr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://aventalearning.com/courses/GEOGx-HS-A09/b/Unit06/GeoHS_6.A.7.html|title=Eastern Europe: Where Is Eastern Europe?|author=|date=|work=aventalearning.com}}</ref>\n\nIn the bay of Dubrovnik is the {{convert|72|ha|adj=on}} wooded island of [[Lokrum]], where according to legend, [[Richard I of England|Richard the Lionheart, King of England]], was cast ashore after being [[shipwreck]]ed in 1192. The island includes a fortress, [[botanical garden]], [[monastery]] and [[Nude beach|naturist beach]].\n\nAmong the many tourist destinations are a few beaches. Banje, Dubrovnik's main public [[beach]], is home to the Eastwest Beach Club. There is also Copacabana Beach, a stony beach on the Lapad peninsula,<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ue-4o37AficC&pg=PA57 |title=Frommer's Croatia |author=Karen Torm\u00e9 Olson |author2=Sanja Bazulic Olson |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |year=2006 |pages=57\u201358 |isbn=0-7645-9898-8 |accessdate=27 October 2009}}</ref> named after the popular beach in [[Copacabana (Rio de Janeiro)|Rio de Janeiro]].\n\nBy 2018, the city had to take steps to reduce the excessive number of tourists, especially in the Old Town. One method to moderate the overcrowding was to stagger the arrival/departure times of cruise ships to spread the number of visitors more evenly during the week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/cruises/news/has-dubrovnik-solved-over-crowding-from-cruise-lines/|title=Has Dubrovnik solved the problem of overcrowding from cruise ships?|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Old City Gallery ===\n{{Gallery cleanup}}\n<gallery>\nFile:Bokar Fortress and the Old Town of Dubrovnik, Croatia (48613181692).jpg|Bokar Fortress and the Old Town of Dubrovnik\nFile:Shopping street Stradun in the historical center of Dubrovnik, Croatia (48613019536).jpg|\"Stradun street\" in the historical center of Dubrovnik\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4031 (37941839474).jpg\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4033 (24787187028).jpg\nFile:Fog over the Old Town of Dubrovnik, Croatia (48613192357).jpg|Fog over the Old Town of Dubrovnik\nFile:The Old Port of Dubrovnik, Croatia (48612660703).jpg|The Old Port of Dubrovnik\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4034 (37941824154).jpg\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4070 (38659653661).jpg\nFile:Historical center of Dubrovnik in Croatia (48612638358).jpg|Historical center of Dubrovnik in Croatia\nFile:Historical center of Dubrovnik with a view to the Lokrum island, Croatia (48613140017).jpg|Historical center of Dubrovnik with a view to the Lokrum island\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4072 (24787085488).jpg\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4074 (24787079488).jpg\nFile:Pile Gate entrance to the Old Town of Dubrovnik, Croatia (48613023636).jpg|Pile Gate entrance to the Old Town of Dubrovnik\nFile:Fort Lovrijenac in Dubrovnik, Croatia (48612678188).jpg|Fort Lovrijenac in Dubrovnik\nFile:Kolorina bay in Dubrovnik, Croatia (48613008056).jpg|Kolorina bay in Dubrovnik\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4075 (38627409632).jpg\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4076 (37941725314).jpg\nFile:Mediterranes Panorama Altstadt von Dubrovnik Ansicht von Osten Hrvatska Kroatien - Foto Wolfgang Pehlemann DSC05194.jpg|Mediterranean panorama of the complete old city of Dubrovnik including city walls and fortifications (photo view from the east)\nFile:Old Port Dubrovnik in Croatia (48613121807).jpg|Old Port Dubrovnik\nFile:Aerial view of Pile Gate in the Old Town of Dubrovnik, Croatia (48613177617).jpg|Aerial view of Pile Gate in the Old Town of Dubrovnik\n</gallery>\n\n===Important monuments===\n[[File:Dubrovnik - roofs.JPG|thumb|right|Rooftops in Dubrovnik's Old City, a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]]]]\n[[File:Old City of Dubrovnik-108792.jpg|thumb|right|Remote view of Dubrovnik Cathedral]]\n[[File:Bokar.jpg|thumb|right|Bokar fortress]]\n[[File:Dalmatia IMG 9840 dubrovnik.JPG|thumb|Aerial view of Dubrovnik from the southwest]]\nFew of Dubrovnik's Renaissance buildings survived the earthquake of 1667 but enough remained to give an idea of the city's architectural heritage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.croatiatraveller.com/southern_dalmatia/Dubrovnik/Dubrovnik_sights.htm |title=Dubrovnik Sights |publisher=Croatia Traveller |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100227091537/http://www.croatiatraveller.com/southern_dalmatia/Dubrovnik/Dubrovnik_sights.htm |archivedate=2010-02-27 |accessdate=2010-02-16 |last=Oliver |first=Jeanne |url-status=dead }}</ref> The finest Renaissance highlight is the [[Sponza Palace]] which dates from the 16th century and is currently used to house the National Archives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dubrovnikcity.com/dubrovnik/attractions/sponza_palace.htm |title=Sponza Palace |publisher=DubrovnikCity.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100414012417/http://www.dubrovnikcity.com/dubrovnik/attractions/sponza_palace.htm |archivedate=2010-04-14 |accessdate=2010-02-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The [[Rector's Palace]] is a Gothic-Renaissance structure that displays finely carved capitals and an ornate staircase. It now houses a museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dubrovnikcity.com/dubrovnik/attractions/rectors_palace.htm |title=The Rector's Palace |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090527112425/http://www.dubrovnikcity.com/dubrovnik/attractions/rectors_palace.htm |archivedate=2009-05-27 |accessdate=2010-02-16 |publisher=DubrovnikCity.com |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dubrovnik-guide.net/rector_palace.htm |title=The Rector's Palace |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611210820/http://dubrovnik-guide.net/rector_palace.htm |publisher=Dubrovnik Guide |archivedate=2010-06-11 |accessdate=2010-02-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Its fa\u00e7ade is depicted on the [[Obverse and reverse|reverse]] of the Croatian 50 [[Croatian kuna|kuna]] banknote, issued in 1993 and 2002.<ref name=\"banknotes1993\"/> The [[St. Saviour Church, Dubrovnik|St. Saviour Church]] is another remnant of the Renaissance period, next to the much-visited [[Franciscan Church and Monastery (Dubrovnik)|Franciscan Church and Monastery]].<ref name=\"dbvonl15\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dubrovnik-guide.net/francisian.htm |title=Franciscan monastery |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611210754/http://dubrovnik-guide.net/francisian.htm |publisher=Dubrovnik Guide |archivedate=2010-06-11 |accessdate=2010-02-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-destinations.com/croatia/dubrovnik-franciscan-monastery.htm |title=Franciscan Friary, Dubrovnik |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117091038/http://www.sacred-destinations.com/croatia/dubrovnik-franciscan-monastery.htm |archivedate=2010-01-17 |accessdate=2010-02-16 |publisher=Sacred Destinations |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Franciscan monastery's library possesses 30,000 volumes, 216 incunabula, 1,500 valuable handwritten documents. Exhibits include a 15th-century silver-gilt cross and silver [[thurible]], and an 18th-century crucifix from Jerusalem, a [[martyrology]] (1541) by Bemardin Gucetic and illuminated [[psalter]]s.<ref name=dbvonl15/>\n\nDubrovnik's most beloved church is [[St Blaise's church]], built in the 18th century in honour of Dubrovnik's patron saint. Dubrovnik's Baroque [[Dubrovnik Cathedral|Cathedral]] was built in the 18th century and houses an impressive Treasury with relics of [[Saint Blaise]]. The city's Dominican Monastery resembles a [[fortress]] on the outside but the interior contains an art museum and a Gothic-Romanesque church.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-destinations.com/croatia/dubrovnik-st-blaise-church.htm |title=Church of St. Blaise, Dubrovnik |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100120024503/http://www.sacred-destinations.com/croatia/dubrovnik-st-blaise-church.htm |archivedate=2010-01-20 |accessdate=2010-02-16 |publisher=Sacred Destinations |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dubrovnik-online.net/english/monuments4.php |title=Monuments (16 to 20) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714093315/http://www.dubrovnik-online.com/english/monuments4.php |archivedate=2010-07-14 |accessdate=2010-02-16 |publisher=Dubrovnik Online |url-status=dead }}</ref> A special treasure of the Dominican monastery is its library with 216 [[incunable|incunabula]], numerous illustrated manuscripts, a rich archive with precious manuscripts and documents and an extensive art collection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-destinations.com/croatia/dubrovnik-dominican-monastery.htm |title=Dominican Friary, Dubrovnik |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102080947/http://sacred-destinations.com/croatia/dubrovnik-dominican-monastery.htm |archivedate=2010-01-02 |accessdate=2010-02-16 |publisher=Sacred Destinations |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.croatiatraveller.com/southern_dalmatia/Dubrovnik/Dominican.htm |title=Dominican Monastery |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104014716/http://croatiatraveller.com/southern_dalmatia/Dubrovnik/Dominican.htm |publisher=Croatia Traveller |last=Oliver |first=Jeanne |archivedate=2010-01-04 |accessdate=2010-02-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dubrovnik-online.net/english/monuments5.php |title=Monuments (21 To 22) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090725060316/http://www.dubrovnik-online.com/english/monuments5.php |publisher=Dubrovnik Online |archivedate=2009-07-25 |accessdate=2010-02-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Neapolitan architect and engineer [[Onofrio della Cava]] completed the aqueduct with two public fountains, both built in 1438. Close to the Pile Gate stands the Big Onofrio's Fountain in the middle of a small square. It may have been inspired by the former Romanesque baptistry of the former cathedral in Buni\u0107 Square. The sculptural elements were lost in the earthquake of 1667. Water jets gush out of the mouth of the sixteen [[Mascaron (architecture)|mascaron]]s. The Little Onofrio's Fountain stands at the eastern side of the Placa, supplying water the market place in the Lu\u017ea Square. The sculptures ware made by the Milanese artist [[Pietro di Martino]] (who also sculpted the ornaments in the Rector's Palace and made a statue \u2013 now lost \u2013 for the Franciscan church).\n\nThe {{convert|31|m|ft|adj=mid|-high}} [[Dubrovnik Bell Tower]], built in 1444, is one of the symbols of the free city state of Ragusa. It was built by the local architects Gruba\u010devi\u0107, Uti\u0161enovi\u0107 and Radon\u010di\u0107. It was rebuilt in 1929 as it had lost its stability through an earthquake and was in danger of falling. The brass face of the clock shows the phases of the moon. Two human figures strike the bell every hour. The tower stands next to the House of the Main Guard, also built in Gothic style. It was the residence of the admiral, commander-in-chief of the army. The Baroque portal was built between 1706 and 1708 by the Venetian architect [[Marino Gropelli]] (who also built St Blaise's church).\n\nIn 1418, the Republic of Ragusa, as Dubrovnik was then named, erected a statue of Roland (Ital. Orlando) as a symbol of loyalty to [[Sigismund, Holy Roman Emperor|Sigismund of Luxembourg]] (1368\u20131437), King of Hungary and Croatia (as of 1387), Prince-Elector of Brandenburg (between 1378 and 1388 and again between 1411 and 1415), German King (as of 1411), King of Bohemia (as of 1419) and Emperor of the Holy Roman Empire (as of 1433), who helped by a successful war alliance against Venice to retain Ragusa's independence. It stands in the middle of Lu\u017ea Square. Roland statues were typical symbols of city autonomy or independence, often erected under Sigismund in his Electorate of Brandenburg. In 1419 the sculptor [[Bonino of Milano]], with the help of local craftsmen, replaced the first Roland with the present Gothic statue. Its forearm was for a long time the unit of measure in Dubrovnik: one [[ell]] of Dubrovnik is equal to {{convert|51.2|cm|1|abbr=on}}.\n\n==== Monuments gallery ====\n{{Gallery cleanup}}\n<gallery>\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 3977 (38603495616).jpg|Big Onofrio's fountain\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4017 (37941866864).jpg|Stradun, the main street of Dubrovnik\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4021 (38659772061).jpg|Old city of Dubrovnik\nFile:Saint Blaise's Church, Dubrovnik - September 2017.jpg|Saint Blaise's Church\nFile:Saint Ignatius Church, Dubrovnik - September 2017.jpg|Saint Ignatius Church\nFile:Main street-Dubrovnik-1.jpg|Stradun, the main street of Dubrovnik\nFile:2011 Dubrownik, Mury miejskie.jpg|City walls\nFile:2011 Dubrownik, Fasada ko\u015bcio\u0142a (02).jpg|Church's fa\u00e7ade\nFile:2011 Dubrownik, Brama Pile (02).jpg|Pile Gate\n</gallery>\n\n===Walls of Dubrovnik===\n{{Main|Walls of Dubrovnik}}\nA feature of Dubrovnik is its walls (1.3 million visitors in 2018), which run almost {{convert|2|km|mi|abbr=off}} around the city. The walls are {{convert|4|to(-)|6|m|ft|0|abbr=off}} thick on the landward side but are much thinner on the seaward side. The system of turrets and towers were intended to protect the vulnerable city. The walls of Dubrovnik have also been a popular filming location for the fictional city of King's Landing in the [[HBO]] television series, ''[[Game of Thrones]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.croatiatraveller.com/southern_dalmatia/Dubrovnik/Walls.htm |title=Dubrovnik's Walls |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104014840/http://croatiatraveller.com/southern_dalmatia/Dubrovnik/Walls.htm |archivedate=2010-01-04 |accessdate=2010-02-16 |publisher=Croatia Traveller |last=Oliver |first=Jeanne |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==== Walls of Dubrovnik Gallery ====\n<gallery>\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4047 (26883590299).jpg\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4053 (38603397226).jpg\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4055 (38627453362).jpg\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4060 (37941777074).jpg\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4071 (38627424862).jpg\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4082 (37941710004).jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|title  = Historical populations<br/> of Dubrovnik\n|shading     = off\n|source = Naselja i stanovni\u0161tvo Republike Hrvatske 1857\u20132001, DZS, Zagreb, 2005\n|1880 |15666\n|1890 |15329\n|1900 |17384\n|1910 |18396\n|1921 |16719\n|1931 |20420\n|1948 |21778\n|1953 |24296\n|1961 |27793\n|1971 |35628\n|1981 |46025\n|1991 |51597\n|2001 |43770\n|2011 |42615\n}}\n[[File:Dubrovnik-F.Tudjman-Bridge.jpg|thumb|right|[[Franjo Tu\u0111man Bridge (Dubrovnik)]]]]\n\nThe total population of the city is 42,615 (census 2011), in the following [[naselje|settlements]]:<ref name=\"census2011\">{{Croatian Census 2011|S|19|0981}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Bosanka]], population 139\n*[[Brse\u010dine]], population 96\n*[[\u010cajkovica]], population 160\n*[[\u010cajkovi\u0107i]], population 26\n*[[Donje Obuljeno]], population 210\n*[[Dubravica, Dubrovnik|Dubravica]], population 37\n* '''Dubrovnik''', population 28,434\n*[[Gornje Obuljeno]], population 124\n*[[Groma\u010da]], population 146\n*[[Kli\u0161evo]], population 54\n*[[Kne\u017eica, Croatia|Kne\u017eica]], population 133\n*[[Kolo\u010dep]], population 163\n*[[Komolac]], population 320\n*[[Lopud]], population 249\n*[[Lozica]], population 146\n*[[Ljuba\u010d, Dubrovnik-Neretva County|Ljuba\u010d]], population 69\n*[[Moko\u0161ica]], population 1,924\n*[[Mravinjac, Croatia|Mravinjac]], population 88\n*[[Mr\u010devo]], population 90\n*[[Moko\u0161ica|Nova Moko\u0161ica]], population 6,016\n*[[Ora\u0161ac, Croatia|Ora\u0161ac]], population 631\n*[[Osojnik, Croatia|Osojnik]], population 301\n*[[Petrovo Selo (Dubrovnik)|Petrovo Selo]], population 23\n*[[Pobre\u017eje, Croatia|Pobre\u017eje]], population 118\n*[[Prijevor, Dubrovnik|Prijevor]], population 453\n*[[Ro\u017eat]], population 340\n*[[Su\u0111ura\u0111]], population 207\n*[[Sustjepan]], population 323\n*[[\u0160ipanska Luka]], population 211\n*[[\u0160umet]], population 176\n*[[Trsteno]], population 222\n*[[Zaton, Dubrovnik-Neretva County|Zaton]], population 985\n{{div col end}}\n\nThe population was 42,615 in 2011,<ref name=\"census2011\"/> down from 49,728 in 1991<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.history.com/encyclopedia.do?articleId=207947 \n |title=Encyclopedia, Dubrovnik \n |work=A&E Television Networks, History.com \n |publisher=Funk & Wagnalls' New Encyclopedia. World Almanac Education Group \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071024083306/http://www.history.com/encyclopedia.do?articleId=207947 \n |archivedate=2007-10-24 \n |accessdate=2010-02-14 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> In the 2011 census, 90.34% of the population identified as [[Croats|Croat]].<ref>{{Croatian Census 2011|E|19}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n[[File:Croatia dbv 3.JPG|thumb|right|[[Dubrovnik Airport]] is the third busiest airport in Croatia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://centreforaviation.com/analysis/dubrovnik-airport-providing-essential--tourism-support-for-a-region-croatia-airlines-3rd-base-297773|title=Dubrovnik Airport: providing essential tourism support for a region. Croatia Airlines' 3rd base|date=22 August 2016|work=centreforaviation.com|accessdate=15 March 2017}}</ref>]]\nDubrovnik has its own [[Dubrovnik Airport|international airport]], located approximately {{convert|20|km|0|abbr=on}} southeast of Dubrovnik city centre, near [[\u010cilipi]]. Buses connect the airport with the Dubrovnik old main [[bus station]] in [[Gru\u017e]]. In addition, a network of modern, local buses connects all Dubrovnik neighbourhoods running frequently from dawn to midnight. However, Dubrovnik, unlike Croatia's other major centres, is not accessible by rail;<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.dubrovnik-online.net/english/transportation_rail.php |title=Transportation Rail |accessdate=20 June 2009 |publisher=Dubrovnik Online}}</ref> until 1975 Dubrovnik was [[Croatian Railways#Dubrovnik|connected]] to [[Mostar]] and [[Sarajevo]] by a [[narrow gauge railway]] (760&nbsp;mm)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.penmorfa.com/JZ/dubrovnik2.html |title=Dubrovnik to Sarajevo 1965 |accessdate=27 September 2011 |publisher=Charlie Lewis}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.penmorfa.com/JZ/jhorsford.html |title=Dubrovnik to Capljina in 1972 |accessdate=27 September 2011 |publisher=Jim Horsford}}</ref> built during the [[Bosnia and Herzegovina (Austro-Hungarian condominium)|Austro-Hungarian rule of Bosnia]].\n\nThe [[A1 (Croatia)|A1]] highway, in use between [[Zagreb]] and [[Plo\u010de]], is planned to be extended all the way to Dubrovnik. Because the area around the city is disconnected from the rest of Croatian territory, the highway will either cross the [[Pelje\u0161ac Bridge]] whose construction is in preparation as of 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://crbc-croatia.com/en/2018/08/23/23-08-2018-2/|title=The examination of the seabed started|publisher=[[China Road and Bridge Corporation]]|date=23 August 2018|accessdate=19 November 2018}}</ref> or run through [[Neum]] in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and continue to Dubrovnik.\n\n=== Harbour gallery ===\n{{Gallery cleanup}}\n<gallery>\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4063 (37941768604).jpg\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4064 (37941760574).jpg\nFile:Dubrovnik D81 4069 (37772024035).jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==Education==\nDubrovnik has a number of higher educational institutions. These include the [[University of Dubrovnik]], the [[Dubrovnik International University|Libertas University]] ([[Dubrovnik International University]]), [[Rochester Institute of Technology Croatia]] (former [[American College of Management and Technology]]),   a University Centre for Postgraduate Studies of the [[University of Zagreb]], and an Institute of History of the [[Croatian Academy of Sciences and Arts]].\n\n==Sports==\nThe city will host the [[2025 World Men's Handball Championship]] at the new arena, along with the countries [[Denmark]] and [[Norway]].\n\n==Notable people==\n\n* [[Franco Sacchetti]] (Ragusa, 1332 \u2013 [[San Miniato]], 1400), poet and novelist \n* [[Benedetto Cotrugli]] (Ragusa, 1416 \u2013 [[L'Aquila]], 1469), humanist and economist.\n* [[Bonino de Boninis]] ([[Lastovo]], Ragusa, 1454 \u2013 [[Treviso]], 1528), typographist and bookseller.\n* [[Elio Lampridio Cerva]] (Ragusa, 1463 \u2013 1520), humanist, poet and lexicographer of [[Latin language]]\n* [[Marin Dr\u017ei\u0107]] (Ragusa, 1508 \u2013 Venice, 1567), playwright, poet and dramaturge\n* {{ill|Nicol\u00f2 Sagri|it}} (Ragusa, ? \u2013 [[Manfredonia]], 1573), mathematician and astronomer\n* [[Marino Ghetaldi]] (Ragusa, 1568 \u2013 1626), mathematician\n* [[Giorgio Raguseo]] (Ragusa, 1580 \u2013 1622),  philosopher, theologian, and orator\n* [[Rajmund Zamanja]] (Ragusa, 1587 \u2013 Ragusa, 1647), theologist, philosopher and linguist.\n* [[Francesco Giovanni Gondola]] (Djivo Gunduli\u0107) (Ragusa, 1588 \u2013 1638), writer and poet, in Shtokavian \n* [[Ivan Gunduli\u0107]] (Ragusa, 1589 \u2013 1638), poet\n* [[Anselmo Banduri]] (Ragusa, 1671 \u2013 [[Paris]], 1743), [[numismatist]] and [[antiquarian]]\n* [[Ru\u0111er Josip Bo\u0161kovi\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1711 \u2013 Milan, 1787) physicist, astronomer, mathematician, philosopher, diplomat, poet, theologian\n* [[Bo\u017eo Bo\u0161kovi\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1815 \u2013 1879)\n* [[Mato Vodopi\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1816), [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Dubrovnik|bishop of Dubrovnik]]\n* [[Matija Ban]] (Dubrovnik, 1818), poet, dramatist, and playwright\n* [[Medo Puci\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1821), writer and politician\n* [[Konstantin Vojnovi\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1832), politician, university professor and rector in the [[Kingdom of Dalmatia]] and [[Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia]] of the [[Habsburg Monarchy]]\n* [[Ivo Vojnovi\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1857), writer\n* [[Dubravka Tom\u0161i\u010d Srebotnjak]] (Dubrovnik, 1940), pianist\n* [[Andro Knego]] (Dubrovnik, 1956), basketball player, Olympic and World champion\n* [[Dragan Andri\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1962), water polo player, two-time Olympic champion\n* [[Nikola Prka\u010din]] (Dubrovnik, 1975), basketball player\n* [[Vlado Georgiev]] (Dubrovnik, 1976), pop singer, composer, and songwriter\n* [[Frano Vi\u0107an]] (Dubrovnik, 1976), water polo player, Olympic, World and European champion\n* [[Emir Spahi\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1980),  football player\n* [[Miho Bo\u0161kovi\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1983), water polo player, Olympic, World and European champion\n* [[Nik\u0161a Dobud]] (Dubrovnik, 1985), water polo player, Olympic and World champion\n* [[Luk\u0161a Andri\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1985), basketball player\n* [[Hrvoje Peri\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1985), basketball player\n* [[Andro Bu\u0161lje]] (Dubrovnik, 1986), water polo player, Olympic, World and European champion\n* [[Paulo Obradovi\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1986), water polo player, Olympic and World champion\n* [[Maro Jokovi\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1987), water polo player, Olympic, World and European champion\n* [[Ante Tomi\u0107 (basketball)|Ante Tomi\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1987), basketball player\n* [[Andrija Prlainovi\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1987), water polo player, Olympic, World and European champion\n* [[Sandro Sukno]] (Dubrovnik, 1990), water polo player, Olympic and World champion\n* [[Mario Hezonja]] (Dubrovnik, 1995), basketball player\n* [[Alen Halilovi\u0107]] (Dubrovnik, 1996), football player\n* [[Ana Konjuh]] (Dubrovnik, 1997), tennis player\n\n==Twin towns - sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Croatia}}\n\nDubrovnik is [[twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Gradovi prijatelji|url=https://www.dubrovnik.hr/gradska-uprava/gradsko-vijece/gradovi-prijatelji|website=dubrovnik.hr|publisher=Dubrovnik|language=hr|accessdate=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Bad Homburg vor der H\u00f6he]], Germany\n*{{flagicon|TUR}} [[Beyo\u011flu]], Turkey\n*{{flagicon|AUT}} [[Graz]], Austria\n*{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Helsingborg Municipality|Helsingborg]], Sweden\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Monterey, California|Monterey]], United States\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Ragusa, Italy|Ragusa]], Italy\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Ravenna]], Italy\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Rueil-Malmaison]], France\n*{{flagicon|CHN}} [[Sanya]], China\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} [[Sarajevo]], Bosnia and Herzegovina\n*{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Venezia]], Italy\n*{{flagicon|CRO}} [[Vukovar]], Croatia\n{{div col end}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe [[HBO]] series ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' used Dubrovnik as a [[filming location]], representing the cities of [[King's Landing (A Song of Ice and Fire)|King's Landing]] and [[Qarth]].<ref>[http://www.jaywaytravel.com/blog/2012/dubrovnik-game-of-thrones/ Dubrovnik in the spotlight] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130311124626/http://www.jaywaytravel.com/blog/2012/dubrovnik-game-of-thrones/ |date=2013-03-11 }}, jaywaytravel.com.</ref> \n\nParts of ''[[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]'' were filmed in Dubrovnik in March 2016, in which Dubrovnik was used as the setting for the casino city of Canto Bight.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.croatiaweek.com/video-star-wars-episode-viii-starts-shooting-in-dubrovnik-this-week/|title=[VIDEO] Star Wars Episode VIII Starts Shooting in Dubrovnik this Week|work=Croatia Week|date=8 March 2016|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/star-wars-bringing-global-prestige-for-dubrovnik-02-12-2016|title=Star Wars Adds Shine to Croatian 'Pearl' Dubrovnik|first=Sven|last=Milekic|publisher=Balkan Insight|date=15 February 2016|accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> \n\nDubrovnik was one of the European sites used in the Bollywood movie ''[[Fan (film)|Fan]]'' (2016), starring [[Shah Rukh Khan]]. \n\nIn early 2017, ''[[Robin Hood (2018 film)|Robin Hood]]'' was filmed on locations in Dubrovnik.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/take-a-look-around-the-set-of-the-new-robin-hood-movie-being-filmed-in-dubrovnik/story-30016420-detail/story.html|title=Take a look around the set of the new Robin Hood movie being filmed in Dubrovnik|date=29 December 2016|work=[[Nottingham Post]]|accessdate=6 March 2017}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn Kander and Ebb's song \"Ring Them Bells,\" the protagonist, Shirley Devore, goes to Dubrovnik to look for a husband and meets her neighbor from New York.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ring Them Bells Lyrics|url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/ring-them-bells-lyrics-liza-minnelli.html|website=MetroLyrics|accessdate=24 October 2017}}</ref> \n\nThe text-based video game ''[[Quarantine Circular]]''<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-05-22-mike-bithell-follows-up-subsurface-circular-with-quarantine-circular | title=Mike Bithell follows up Subsurface Circular with Quarantine Circular | work=[[Eurogamer]] | first=Wesley | last=Yin-Poole | date=2018-05-22 | accessdate=2018-05-22}}</ref> is set aboard a ship off the coast of Dubrovnik, and a few references to the city are made throughout the course of the game.\n\nThe [[Dubrovniks]] were an Australian Independent rock band formed in 1987. Often regarded as a 'Supergroup' due to the band members having played in various established bands such as [[Hoodoo Gurus]], [[Beasts of Bourbon]], and [[The Scientists]]. The band chose their name due to two members of the band [[Roddy Radalj]] (guitar vocals) and Boris Sujdovik (bass) being born in Dubrovnik.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia | last = McFarlane | first = Ian | authorlink = Ian McFarlane | encyclopedia = [[Encyclopedia of Australian Rock and Pop]] | title = Whammo Homepage | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20040405231007/http://www.whammo.com.au/index.asp | url = http://www.whammo.com.au/index.asp | archivedate = 5 April 2004 | accessdate = 4 May 2014 | year = 1999 | publisher = [[Allen & Unwin]] | location = [[St Leonards, New South Wales|St Leonards, NSW]] | isbn = 1-86508-072-1 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Croatia}}\n*[[Dalmatia]]\n*[[Dubrovnik chess set]]\n*[[List of people from Dubrovnik]]\n*[[Republic of Ragusa]]\n*[[Tourism in Croatia]]\n*[[Walls of Dubrovnik]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n*{{Cite book |author=Peterjon Cresswell |author2=Ismay Atkins |author3=Lily Dunn |last-author-amp=yes |title=Time Out Croatia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VZweAAAACAAJ |accessdate=10 March 2010 |year=2006 |publisher=Time Out Group Ltd. & Ebury Publishing, [[Random House|Random House Ltd.]] |edition=First |location=London, Berkeley & Toronto |isbn=978-1-904978-70-1 }}\n*{{cite book |author=Robin Harris |title=Dubrovnik, A History |location=London |publisher=Saqi Books |year=2003 |isbn=0-86356-332-5 }}\n*{{cite book |editor=Adriana Kremenja\u0161-Dani\u010di\u0107 |title=Roland's European Paths |location=Dubrovnik |publisher=Europski dom Dubrovnik |year=2006 |isbn=953-95338-0-5 }}\n*{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/2716347.stm |title=Dubrovnik's Heritage Under Threat |author=Marko Kovac |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=February 4, 2003 }}\n*{{Cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/features/2008/0718/1216073242375.html |title=The 'Pearl' loses its lustre |author=Frank McDonald |work=[[The Irish Times]] |date=July 18, 2008 | accessdate=March 2, 2017}}\n*{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/06/07/style/will-greed-tarnish-croatias-gem.html?_r=0 |title=Will greed tarnish Croatia's gem? |author=Joshua Wright |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 7, 2004 | accessdate=March 2, 2017 }}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Vojnovi\u0107|first=Lujo|title=Pad Dubrovnika (1797.-1806.)|publisher=Fortuna|isbn=978-953-95981-9-6|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YhlJAQAAMAAJ&dq=|year=2009}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Citation |publisher = W.J. Adams |location = London |title = Bradshaw's Hand-Book to the Turkish Empire |volume=1: Turkey in Europe |date = c. 1872 |chapter= Ragusa |chapterurl= https://books.google.com/books?id=shMIAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA346 |title-link = Bradshaw's Guide }}\n* {{Citation |publisher = [[Sampson Low, Marston, Searle, & Rivington]] |series=Foreign Countries and British Colonies |location = London |title = Austria-Hungary |author = David Kay |date = 1880 |chapter=Principal Towns: Ragusa |hdl=2027/mdp.39015030647005 }}\n*{{Cite book |publisher = [[Murray's Handbooks for Travellers|J. Murray]] |location = London |author = R. Lambert Playfair |author-link = Lambert Playfair |title = Handbook to the Mediterranean |edition=3rd |date = 1892 |chapterurl= https://archive.org/stream/handbooktomedit01firgoog#page/n45/mode/2up |chapter= Ragusa }}\n*{{Cite book |title = Austria-Hungary, Including Dalmatia and Bosnia |publisher = Karl Baedeker |location=Leipzig |date = 1905 |oclc = 344268 |chapterurl= https://archive.org/stream/austriahungaryi00firgoog#page/n476/mode/2up |chapter= Ragusa }}\n*{{Cite book |publisher = McClurg & Co |author = F. K. Hutchinson |location = Chicago |title = Motoring in the Balkans |date = 1909 |oclc = 8647011 |chapter= Ragusa |ol = 13515412M }}\n* {{cite book |editor=Trudy Ring |title=Southern Europe |series=International Dictionary of Historic Places |volume=3 |year= 1996 |publisher=Fitzroy Dearborn |oclc=31045650 |chapter=Dubrovnik }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Dubrovnik}}\n* {{official|http://www.dubrovnik.hr/}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051225201018/https://whc.unesco.org/PG.CFM?cid=31&id_site=95 UNESCO World Heritage Centre: Old City of Dubrovnik]\n* [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/172803/Dubrovnik/ Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica.com: Dubrovnik]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sQegEro5Bfo Youtube.com: Dubrovnik \u2014 digital video reconstruction] \u2014 ''by GRAIL at Washington University''.\n*{{Wiktionary-inline}}\n*{{Wikivoyage-inline}}\n\n{{County seats of Croatia}}\n{{Subdivisions of Dubrovnik-Neretva County}}\n{{Croatian cities}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in Croatia}}\n{{Repubbliche Marinare}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Dubrovnik| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Capitals of former nations]]\n[[Category:Dalmatia]]\n[[Category:Mediterranean port cities and towns in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Dubrovnik-Neretva County]]\n[[Category:Fortified settlements]]\n[[Category:Kingdom of Dalmatia]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 7th century]]\n[[Category:7th-century establishments in Europe]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Danger]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Ports and harbours of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Territories of the Republic of Venice]]\n", "name_user": "Doeze", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added link for Canto Bight", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dubrovnik"}
{"title_page": "George Iles", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = George Iles\n|fullname       = George Frederick Iles\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        = \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|C}}\n|birth_date    = 28 March, 1894\n|birth_place = Christchurch, New Zealand\n|death_date    = 27 March, 1933\n|death_place = Tauranga, New Zealand (aged 39)\n|height         =  \n|weight         =\n|ru_club1            = Tauranga Football Club\n|ru_year1start       = 1920\n|ru_year1end         = 22\n|ru_appearances1     =16\n|ru_tries1           =9\n|ru_goals1           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals1      =0\n|ru_points1          =27\n|ru_club2            = Cadets Old Boys (Tau.)\n|ru_year2start       = 1923\n|ru_year2end         = \n|ru_appearances2     =4\n|ru_tries2           =2\n|ru_goals2           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals2      =0\n|ru_points2          =6 \n|ru_club3            = Athletic (Tau.)\n|ru_year3start       = 1929\n|ru_year3end         = 30\n|ru_appearances3     =\n|ru_tries3           =1\n|ru_goals3           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals3      =0\n|ru_points3          =3\n|ru_teamA            = Tauranga (Rep)\n|ru_yearAstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearAend         = 23\n|ru_appearancesA     =9\n|ru_triesA           =7\n|ru_goalsA           =0\n|ru_fieldgoalsA      =0\n|ru_pointsA          =21\n|ru_teamB            = [[Auckland rugby union team|Auckland]]\n|ru_yearBstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearBend         = \n|ru_appearancesB     = 1\n|ru_triesB           = 0\n|ru_goalsB           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsB      = 0\n|ru_pointsB          =0\n|ru_teamC            = [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]]\n|ru_yearCstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearCend         = \n|ru_appearancesC     = 1\n|ru_triesC           = 2\n|ru_goalsC           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsC      = 0\n|ru_pointsC          =3\n|club1          = [[Grafton Athletic]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1915\n|year1end       = \n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 3\n|club2               = [[Newton Rangers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year2start          = 1916\n|year2end            = 19\n|appearances2        = \n|tries2              = 33\n|goals2              = 4\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 107\n|club3               = Tauranga RL\n|year3start          = 1922\n|year3end            = \n|appearances3        = 2\n|tries3              = 1\n|goals3              = 0\n|fieldgoals3         =0\n|points3             = 3\n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 4\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          = 1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 4\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             =  3\n|teamC               = [[Bay of Plenty rugby league team|Bay of Plenty]]\n|yearCstart          = 1922\n|yearCend            =  \n|appearancesC        = 2\n|triesC              = 1\n|goalsC              = 0\n|fieldgoalsC         = 0\n|pointsC             =  3\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nGeorge Iles was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921. In 1922 he made an effort to establish Rugby League in the Tauranga area which failed however he did play matches for Tauranga and a Bay of Plenty league team who played against Auckland and the touring [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] team.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Harriet and Albert Iles, whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League and Rugby Union Playing Career==\n===Auckland and New Zealand Rugby League===\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n===Move to Tauranga and Switch to Rugby Union===\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In a bizarre situation Iles played for Auckland against his own Bay of Plenty union in a match on 31 July when an Auckland back was unable to make the trip to Tauranga and Iles was asked to take his place. Bay of Plenty won 17-10 but Iles played brilliantly and comment was made that he shouldn't have been left out of the Bay team in the first place\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Bay of Plenty Footballers Defeat Auckland Representatives\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7464, 2 August 1920, Page 3\n| date = 1920-08-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200802.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In September Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nIsles was playing for the Tauranga Football Club in the Jordan Cup competition for clubs and he also regularly appeared for the Tauranga representative team in Kusab Cup fixtures. His debut season in the code continued to be an impressive one. In a match for Tauranga against Te Puke in the Kusab Cup he ran in 3 tries in a 9-6 win\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Football Contest in Te Puke on Saturday for the Kusab Cup\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7474, 16 August 1920, Page 2\n| date = 1920-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200816.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. During the 1921 Kusab Cup he played in matches against Mercury Bay<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, Te Puke<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kusabs' Cup Match Next Saturday\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7710\n| date = 1921-06-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210602.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, [[Whakatane]] in the semi final, and Rotorua in the final. Tauranga won the Cup when they defeated Rotorua 16-9 at Arawa Park, [[Rotorua]] after several years of trying with Iles captaining the team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Wins Kusabs' Cup Final/Rotorua Beaten by Sixteen Points to Nine\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7742\n| date = 1921-07-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210711.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nHowever Iles greatest achievement of the year was on the 16th of August when he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to David Werahiko Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n===Effort to Introduce Rugby League to Tauranga===\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the [[Tauranga]] area in 1922. The Tauranga Rugby League was started and they looked to play rugby league teams from other areas. The league was officially formed in March, 1922 <ref>{{cite news| title = Under League Rules/Decisions of Executive\n| page = 3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LIX, Issue 18053, 30 March 1922, Page 3\n| date = 1922-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220330.2.16.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They made efforts to organise a game with the newly formed Rotorua league team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8079\n| date = 1922-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220902.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was still playing rugby union through this period and played for Tauranga in a drawn match with Rangataua in June\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Union's Cup Matches Continued/Tauranga and Rangataua Play a Draw\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8007\n| date = 1922-06-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220612.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nOn the 16th of September history was made in Tauranga with the first ever game of rugby keague played there. Tauranga took on the Rotorua team on the Tauranga Domain. As well as George Iles playing, David Borell and Arthur Iles also played in the match. Rotorua won a high scoring match 29-28 with both Iles and Borell scoring tries\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rotorua Wins by One Point\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8092\n| date = 1922-09-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220918.2.24\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nA game against the touring [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] was also arranged which was a remarkable achievement in itself given that rugby league was not even played in the area until a month earlier. The match was between New South Wales and Bay of Plenty. George Iles naturally played and the team also featured future Kiwi [[George Gardiner (rugby league)|George Gardiner]] while the visiting NSW team featured the likes of [[Frank Burge]] and [[Reg Latta]]. New South Wales won the match 29 points to 5 with Borell scoring a try and Joseph Rogers kicking a goal for the local team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kangaroos 29 Bay of Plenty 5\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8101\n| date = 1922-09-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220928.2.33\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>.\n\nOn September 30 Tauranga again made history by playing in the first ever rugby league game in [[Te Puke]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Efforts were then made to arrange a match with an Auckland team and this eventuated with Auckland sending a very strong team down to play in Tauranga on October 7. It wasn\u2019t a Tauranga side who took on Auckland rather a Bay of Plenty team with players from throughout the district. George Iles captained the Bay of Plenty side and they performed well only going down 27-33 to an Auckland team which featured a large number of New Zealand international players such as [[Clarrie Polson]], [[Wally Somers]], and future Kiwi\u2019s [[Lou Brown (rugby league)|Lou Brown]], [[Neville St George]], and [[James Lawrence O\u2019Brien|Jim Brown]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland League Team in Tauranga/Match Against Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| work = Bay of Plenty Times| volume=LI| issue=8109\n| date = 1922-10-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19221007.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>. Iles scored a try against his former team.\n\nIn September Iles went on the attack again, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On October 14 Tauranga played a match on the Waihi Recreation Ground and lost 6-19 in front of a large attendance, Iles again leading the Tauranga team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Waihi-Tauranga League Match\n| page =2\n| publisher =Waihi Daily Telegraph, Volume XX, Issue 6741\n| date = 1922-10-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WHDT19221016.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>. These efforts to grow the game in the area, while somewhat remarkable, ultimately proved futile and Iles returned to the rugby union field the following season.\n\n===Back to Rugby Union===\nIn 1923 he played for Tauranga rugby team against Te Puke in Te Puke and then again in the return match in Tauranga. He was also turning out for the Cadets Old Boys senior side in the club competition <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football on Monday Next/Te Puke Representatives to Visit Tauranga\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8302\n| date = 1923-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230531.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He scored 2 tries for Cadets in an 11-8 win over Rangataua\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Local and General\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8305\n| date = 1923-06-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230605.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1924 he played for Tauranga against Te Puke in a Kusab's Cup match won by Tauranga 8-6\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Brilliant Game for Kusab's Cup\n| page = 5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LII, Issue 8633\n| date = 1924-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19240714.2.21\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played another match for them against Te Puke in June 1925, and captained Tauranga against [[Rangitaiki]] in 1925 to a 12-5 victory with Iles involved prominently throughout the match <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga v Te Puke\n| page =6\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19039\n| date = 1925-06-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250609.2.10.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Match Won by Tauranga/Good Game Against Rangitaiki Team\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIII, Issue 8935\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250720.2.25\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the rugby season he joined the Tauranga Rowing Club, being elected a member on 26 September at their AGM\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rowing Club/Annual General Meeting\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 8994\n| date = 1925-09-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250926.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles represented Tauranga against [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was playing for the Cadets Old Boys club this season\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rugby Union Championships\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 9179\n| date = 1929-05-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19260510.2.30\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He played for Tauranga against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nOn July 27, 1929 Tauranga beat Opotiki for the Hurinui Apanui Shield with Iles playing<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Apanui Shield/Tauranga Defeats Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10137\n| date = 1929-07-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290729.2.10\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The Hurinui Apanui Shield was named after the famous Ngatiawa chief who had died in 1924 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Death of Hurinui Apanui\n| page =5\n| publisher =King Country Chronicle, Volume XIX, Issue 1967\n| date = 1924-05-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/KCC19240524.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. A week later they defended it against Rotorua with Iles playing five eighth\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Shield Match/Rotorua V Tauranga\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10147\n| date = 1929-08-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290809.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Despite being 35 years of age by this point Iles was heavily involved in a 17-0 win playing with his \"characteristic cleverness\"\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Union Retains Shield/Keen Rugby Game on Domain/Rotorua Defeated\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10149\n| date = 1929-08-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290812.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His younger brother Eric was playing alongside him in the backs through all of these matches. Eric would himself go on the represent the Bay of Plenty rugby team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Management Committee\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played again in the defence against Taupo on August 24 which they won 27-11 and again in early September against Opotiki <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Huinui Apanui Shield Game/Tauranga Defeats Taupo/A Good Margin\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10161\n| date = 1929-08-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290826.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Team to Play Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10168\n| date = 1929-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290903.2.11\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They drew the match 6-6 with a penalty after the full time bell which meant they retained the shield for the summer as it was the last challenge of the year\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Hurinui Apanui Shield Match/Spectacular Game Ends in Even Score\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10173\n| date = 1929-09-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290909.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the start of the 1930 season Iles was appointed the backs coach with J. Duncan coaching the forwards for the Tauranga team <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His coaching career did not begin well with the team losing the match 3-6 to Te Puke, and the Hurinui Apanui Shield in the process <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Game for the Te Hurinui Apanui Shield/Te Puke Defeats Tauranga by Six to Three\n| page = 3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10403\n| date = 1930-06-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300616.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIles was a member of the Athletic Football Club from 1928 onwards with his brother Arthur on the management committee <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Athletic Club\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10049\n| date = 1929-04-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290415.2.12\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They had been named College Old Boys until 1928 when they changed to the Athletic name <ref>{{cite news\n| title =A Name Changed\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVI, Issue 9766\n| date = 1928-04-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19280423.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles was playing for their senior team along with his brother Eric\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tomorrow's Games\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10088\n| date = 1929-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290531.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1930 George had turned his hand to refereeing in the Jordan Cup for senior club teams\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. However he was still playing, turning out for Athletic against Cadets in the Jordan Cup and scoring a try in a 6-9 loss\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Union's Cup Competitions\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10415\n| date = 1930-06-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300630.2.20\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. By 1932 George had become the club captain and still writing letters to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Football Criticism\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LXI, Issue 10905\n| date = 1932-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19320903.2.11.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920 exporting \"hides, calf skins, sheepskins, wool, tallow, horsehair etc\" <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They were based on Willow St., Tauranga with depots in [[Te Puke]], [[Whakatane]], and [[Taneatua]] and acted as agents for Wilson and Canham <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Iles Bros\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7349\n| date = 1920-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200301.2.3.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 one day before what would have been his 40th birthday, after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow Grace Malya Iles, who he had wed in 1927, and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Christchurch]]\n[[Category:Bay of Plenty rugby union players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rugby league biography\n|name     = George Iles\n|fullname       = George Frederick Iles\n|nickname       = \n|image          = \n|image_size     =\n|caption        =\n|country        = \n|position       = {{rlp|WG|C}}\n|birth_date    = 28 March, 1894\n|birth_place = Christchurch, New Zealand\n|death_date    = 27 March, 1933\n|death_place = Tauranga, New Zealand (aged 39)\n|height         =  \n|weight         =\n|ru_club1            = Tauranga Football Club\n|ru_year1start       = 1920\n|ru_year1end         = 22\n|ru_appearances1     =16\n|ru_tries1           =9\n|ru_goals1           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals1      =0\n|ru_points1          =27\n|ru_club2            = Cadets Old Boys (Tau.)\n|ru_year2start       = 1923\n|ru_year2end         = \n|ru_appearances2     =4\n|ru_tries2           =2\n|ru_goals2           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals2      =0\n|ru_points2          =6 \n|ru_club3            = Athletic (Tau.)\n|ru_year3start       = 1929\n|ru_year3end         = 30\n|ru_appearances3     =\n|ru_tries3           =1\n|ru_goals3           =0\n|ru_fieldgoals3      =0\n|ru_points3          =3\n|ru_teamA            = Tauranga (Rep)\n|ru_yearAstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearAend         = 23\n|ru_appearancesA     =9\n|ru_triesA           =7\n|ru_goalsA           =0\n|ru_fieldgoalsA      =0\n|ru_pointsA          =21\n|ru_teamB            = [[Auckland rugby union team|Auckland]]\n|ru_yearBstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearBend         = \n|ru_appearancesB     = 1\n|ru_triesB           = 0\n|ru_goalsB           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsB      = 0\n|ru_pointsB          =0\n|ru_teamC            = [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]]\n|ru_yearCstart       = 1920\n|ru_yearCend         = \n|ru_appearancesC     = 1\n|ru_triesC           = 2\n|ru_goalsC           = 0\n|ru_fieldgoalsC      = 0\n|ru_pointsC          =3\n|club1          = [[Grafton Athletic]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year1start     = 1915\n|year1end       = \n|appearances1   = \n|tries1         = 1\n|goals1         = 0\n|fieldgoals1    =0 \n|points1        = 3\n|club2               = [[Newton Rangers]] [[Auckland Rugby League|(ARL)]]\n|year2start          = 1916\n|year2end            = 19\n|appearances2        = \n|tries2              = 33\n|goals2              = 4\n|fieldgoals2         =0\n|points2             = 107\n|club3               = Tauranga RL\n|year3start          = 1922\n|year3end            = \n|appearances3        = 2\n|tries3              = 1\n|goals3              = 0\n|fieldgoals3         =0\n|points3             = 3\n|teamA          = [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]]\n|yearAstart     = 1918\n|yearAend       = 19\n|appearancesA   = 4\n|triesA         = 5\n|goalsA         = 0\n|fieldgoalsA    =0 \n|pointsA        = 15\n|teamB               = [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]]\n|yearBstart          = 1919\n|yearBend            =  \n|appearancesB        = 4\n|triesB              = 1\n|goalsB              = 0\n|fieldgoalsB         = 0\n|pointsB             =  3\n|teamC               = [[Bay of Plenty rugby league team|Bay of Plenty]]\n|yearCstart          = 1922\n|yearCend            =  \n|appearancesC        = 2\n|triesC              = 1\n|goalsC              = 0\n|fieldgoalsC         = 0\n|pointsC             =  3\n|updated        = \n|source         =|new            = yes\n}}\n\nGeorge Iles was a winger and centre who played for the [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] rugby league team. He debuted for them in 1919 and became Kiwi number 125<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kiwis Roll of Honour\n| publisher = New Zealand Rugby League\n| url =https://nzrl.co.nz/kiwis-home/past-kiwis/\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He played his club rugby league for the [[Grafton Athletic]] and [[Newton Rangers]] teams in the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition. He later moved to [[Tauranga]] and played for Tauranga and [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] at rugby union including against the touring [[Springbok national rugby union team|Springbok]] team in 1921. In 1922 he made an effort to establish Rugby League in the Tauranga area which failed however he did play matches for Tauranga and a Bay of Plenty league team who played against Auckland.\n\n==Early Life==\nGeorge Iles grew up in [[Christchurch]]. He was the son of Harriet and Albert Iles, whose parents had come to New Zealand in one of the first \u201cfour ships\u201d which brought settlers to [[Canterbury, New Zealand|Canterbury]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-09}}</ref>.\nAlbert was a successful sportsman in his own right captaining the Sydenham Football Club in the 1880s and representing [[Canterbury Rugby Football Union|Canterbury]] and [[Rugby Southland|Southland]] for several years. He was also a champion runner. In 1912 the family moved to [[Auckland]] where they lived until 1919 and it was during these years that George made a name for himself as a rugby league player.\n\n==Rugby League and Rugby Union Playing Career==\n===Auckland and New Zealand Rugby League===\nGeorge Iles began his playing career for [[Grafton Athletic]] with his name first appearing in a team list for their second grade team in 1914 along with his brother Arthur Iles <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Under League Rules/Fixtures and Teams/Grafton Club\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LI, Issue 15621\n| date = 1914-05-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19140529.2.132.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The following season he debuted for the Grafton senior team and played in the [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|Auckland first grade competition]]. He was fortunate to play alongside the likes of New Zealand rugby league legends [[Karl Ifwersen]] and [[Dougie McGregor]], the later having already played for the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] rugby team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game Notes and Comments\n| page = 10\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LII, Issue 15915\n| date = 1915-05-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19150512.2.124.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Grafton were to win the Auckland title [[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|this season]].\n\nBoth George and Arthur were to transfer to the [[Newton Rangers]] team for the [[1916 Auckland Rugby League season|1916 season]]. Newton struggled and finished last however Iles did score 7 out of Newton\u2019s 20 tries making him the second highest try scorer for the entire competition. The following year he went even better scoring 12 tries and leading the try scorer lists in the [[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917 competition]].\n\nIn 1918 Iles scored 4 tries for Newton and was also elected secretary of the club at their annual meeting<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Newton Rangers Club\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16814\n| date = 1918-04-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180403.2.60\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He gained his first representative jersey when he was selected for the [[Auckland rugby league team|Auckland]] team for, at that time, a very rare representative fixture. During the war years the [[Auckland Rugby League]] had deliberately played almost no representative matches. The match was against [[Canterbury rugby league team|Canterbury]] and played at the [[Auckland Domain]] in front of 10,000 spectators. Auckland won 45-9 with Iles scoring a try in the corner \u201cafter a cross-field run\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland Defeats Canterbury/Forty-Five Points to Nine\n| page =3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LV, Issue 16956\n| date = 1918-09-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19180916.2.15.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>.\n\nOnce again in [[1919 Auckland Rugby League season|1919]] Iles was a prolific try scorer for Newton notching 10 tries in total including tries in the Roope Rooster semi final against [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]], and the semi final replay against the same opponents when the first match was abandoned near the end after Ponsonby fans encroached on the field and refused to move. Newton went on to win the Roope Rooster for the first time in their clubs history<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Roope Rooster Competition/Final Won by Newton/Game Played in Downpour\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>. \n\nIles was picked to play for Auckland against New Zealand on May 24. It was the first of 3 games he would play for them this season. The match was a warmup for the Australian Tour for the New Zealand side and was won by New Zealand 25-19 in front of 8,000 spectators at the [[Auckland Domain]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =New Zealand Beats Auckland/Keenly Contested Game\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17170\n| date = 1919-05-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190526.2.105.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His next appearance was against the Returned Soldiers team as part of the Peace Day celebration program. It was held at the Auckland Domain on July 20 and featured athletics, rugby union, rugby league, football, and hockey matches. The Returned Soldiers team won 26-24 with Iles scoring two second half tries for the losing Auckland team<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Northern Union Grade\n| page =9\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume L, Issue 172\n| date = 1919-07-22\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19190722.2.130\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>. His last ever match in an Auckland jersey was played against [[Rugby League Hawkes Bay|Hawke\u2019s Bay]] at [[Eden Park]] on August 9 with 9,000 watching on. Iles scored two more tries. The first after receiving a pass from [[Bert Laing]] and \u201ccutting in neatly and scoring\u201d, while his second saw him picking up the ball in the open \u201coutpacing the opposition and swerving past McCarthy [to score] a good try\u201d<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Representative Match/Auckland V Hawke\u2019s Bay\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17235\n| date = 1911-08-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190811.2.111.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-18}}</ref>.\n\nIles was to make his [[New Zealand national rugby league team|New Zealand]] debut two weeks later. He played all of his 4 matches for New Zealand in 4 consecutive weekends. New Zealand had sent a touring team to [[Australia]] where they had played 11 matches against various teams but no tests<ref>{{cite news\n| title = All Blacks Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/all-blacks-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. After this tour they returned home and [[Australia national rugby league team|Australia]] sent a touring team to New Zealand<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kangaroos Tour 1919\n| publisher = Rugby League Project\n| url = https://www.rugbyleagueproject.org/competitions/kangaroos-tour-1919/summary.html\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had played in a trial on May 14 to make the tour but was not selected.\n\nOn August 23 he played his first test for New Zealand at the [[Basin Reserve]] in [[Wellington]] and went down 21-44 in front of 8,000 spectators<ref>{{cite news\n| title = League Football/Australia V New Zealand\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 282\n| date = 1919-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190825.2.88\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles had a happier time of it in the second test which New Zealand won at Sydenham Park in [[Christchurch]]. Iles scored a try which was described \u201cfollowing an exchange of kicks between the two full-backs the New Zealanders swept down in a line and Iles got over\u201d, this made the score 21-2 to New Zealand. They would go on to win 26-10 in front of 6,000<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The League Game/Australia v New Zealand/Visitors Outclassed\n| page = 7\n| publisher = Dominion, Volume 12, Issue 288\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/DOM19190901.2.78\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The third test was played in Auckland at the Domain with a huge crowd of 24,300 present to see New Zealand go down 23-34<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Third League Test/Australia v New Zealand/Win for the Visitors/Score 34 Points to 23/Fast and Open Game\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17259\n| date = 1919-09-08\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190908.2.119\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. While Iles 4th and final appearance for New Zealand came at the Auckland Domain once again with New Zealand being trounced 2-32 to lose the series 1-3<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Australia v New Zealand\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17265\n| date = 1919-09-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190915.2.130\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. Iles was listed to play in the reserves a week later for the Auckland team to play Australia but he did not take the field in an 8-32 loss.\n\n===Move to Tauranga and Switch to Rugby Union===\nIn 1920 George Iles moved to Tauranga with his family. There because rugby league was barely played he largely played rugby union over the following decade for Tauranga and the [[Bay of Plenty Steamers|Bay of Plenty]] representative team. In July 1920 he played for Tauranga against Grammar Old Boys. It was said \u201cof the Tauranga team the Isles [sic] brothers, three quarters, played well, and if supported by other members of the back division, would have made things a bit more awkward for the visitors. They both handled the ball well\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Grammar Old Boys v Tauranga\n| page = 8\n| publisher = Observer, Volume XL, Issue 45\n| date = 1920-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/TO19200710.2.13.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. In a bizarre situation Iles played for Auckland against his own Bay of Plenty union in a match on 31 July when an Auckland back was unable to make the trip to Tauranga and Iles was asked to take his place. Bay of Plenty won 17-10 but Iles played brilliantly and comment was made that he shouldn't have been left out of the Bay team in the first place\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Bay of Plenty Footballers Defeat Auckland Representatives\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7464, 2 August 1920, Page 3\n| date = 1920-08-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200802.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In September Iles made a return to [[Eden Park]], this time in a Bay of Plenty rugby jersey where they were defeated 17-34 to Auckland. Iles set up Bay of Plenty\u2019s first try and then scored two himself<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Auckland V Bay of Plenty/The Visitors Defeated\n| page = 7\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVII, Issue 17580\n| date = 1920-09-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200920.2.106\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nIsles was playing for the Tauranga Football Club in the Jordan Cup competition for clubs and he also regularly appeared for the Tauranga representative team in Kusab Cup fixtures. His debut season in the code continued to be an impressive one. In a match for Tauranga against Te Puke in the Kusab Cup he ran in 3 tries in a 9-6 win\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Football Contest in Te Puke on Saturday for the Kusab Cup\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7474, 16 August 1920, Page 2\n| date = 1920-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200816.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. During the 1921 Kusab Cup he played in matches against Mercury Bay<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Match at Tauranga\n| page = 9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVIII, Issue 17836\n| date = 1921-07-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210718.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, Te Puke<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kusabs' Cup Match Next Saturday\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7710\n| date = 1921-06-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210602.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>, [[Whakatane]] in the semi final, and Rotorua in the final. Tauranga won the Cup when they defeated Rotorua 16-9 at Arawa Park, [[Rotorua]] after several years of trying with Iles captaining the team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Wins Kusabs' Cup Final/Rotorua Beaten by Sixteen Points to Nine\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7742\n| date = 1921-07-11\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210711.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nHowever Iles greatest achievement of the year was on the 16th of August when he was selected to play for Bay of Plenty against the touring Springbok team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7773\n| date = 1921-08-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210816.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The match was played at [[Rotorua]] with 5,000 spectators present to witness the Springboks win by 17 points to 9. Iles helped set up the first try to David Werahiko Borell after he initiated a \u201cnice attack\u201d and he did the same for their second and final try when Montgomery \u201csent the ball across to Iles who opened up splendidly, and the ball came across to Borell, who scored near the corner\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Springboks Beat Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume 49, Issue 7781\n| date = 1921-08-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19210825.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n===Effort to Introduce Rugby League to Tauranga===\nDespite these fine rugby achievements it appears that Iles had not forgotten his rugby league background. He was part of an effort to establish rugby league in the [[Tauranga]] area in 1922. The Tauranga Rugby League was started and they looked to play rugby league teams from other areas. The league was officially formed in March, 1922 <ref>{{cite news| title = Under League Rules/Decisions of Executive\n| page = 3\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LIX, Issue 18053, 30 March 1922, Page 3\n| date = 1922-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220330.2.16.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They made efforts to organise a game with the newly formed Rotorua league team<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8079\n| date = 1922-09-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220902.2.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. On April 12 he wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] about the strength of the rugby league code in various places and was writing in response to a query about why rugby league had been started in the area by Mr. Phelan, a past member of the Tauranga rugby selection committee. Iles responded in a lengthy letter \u201cthe answer is the same as that to why the League game was first commenced \u2013 that is dissatisfaction with Rugby management\u201d, he went on to say \u201ctouching on the standard of play in League, as one who has played both codes I give it as my opinion that League is played on a far higher standard in [[Australia]] and [[Auckland]] than Rugby\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Public Opinion/Rival Codes\n| page = 4\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 7961\n| date = 1922-04-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220413.2.27\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was still playing rugby union through this period and played for Tauranga in a drawn match with Rangataua in June\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Union's Cup Matches Continued/Tauranga and Rangataua Play a Draw\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8007\n| date = 1922-06-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220612.2.5\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On August 28 he wrote another letter suggesting a match between those players who had been selected for the Tauranga rugby union team and those who had not as there had evidently been some controversy over selections<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Challenge\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume L, Issue 8075\n| date = 1922-08-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220829.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nOn the 16th of September history was made in Tauranga with the first ever game of rugby keague played there. Tauranga took on the Rotorua team on the Tauranga Domain. As well as George Iles playing, David Borell and Arthur Iles also played in the match. Rotorua won a high scoring match 29-28 with both Iles and Borell scoring tries\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rotorua Wins by One Point\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8092\n| date = 1922-09-18\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220918.2.24\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nA game against the touring [[New South Wales rugby league team|New South Wales]] was also arranged which was a remarkable achievement in itself given that rugby league was not even played in the area until a month earlier. The match was between New South Wales and Bay of Plenty. George Iles naturally played and the team also featured future Kiwi [[George Gardiner (rugby league)|George Gardiner]] while the visiting NSW team featured the likes of [[Frank Burge]] and [[Reg Latta]]. New South Wales won the match 29 points to 5 with Borell scoring a try and Joseph Rogers kicking a goal for the local team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Kangaroos 29 Bay of Plenty 5\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8101\n| date = 1922-09-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220928.2.33\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>.\n\nOn September 30 Tauranga again made history by playing in the first ever rugby league game in [[Te Puke]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Local and General\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Efforts were then made to arrange a match with an Auckland team and this eventuated with Auckland sending a very strong team down to play in Tauranga on October 7. It wasn\u2019t a Tauranga side who took on Auckland rather a Bay of Plenty team with players from throughout the district. George Iles captained the Bay of Plenty side and they performed well only going down 27-33 to an Auckland team which featured a large number of New Zealand international players such as [[Clarrie Polson]], [[Wally Somers]], and future Kiwi\u2019s [[Lou Brown (rugby league)|Lou Brown]], [[Neville St George]], and [[James Lawrence O\u2019Brien|Jim Brown]].<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Auckland League Team in Tauranga/Match Against Bay of Plenty\n| page = 3\n| work = Bay of Plenty Times| volume=LI| issue=8109\n| date = 1922-10-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19221007.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-03-11}}</ref>. Iles scored a try against his former team.\n\nIn September Iles went on the attack again, this time in response to the suggestion by rugby supporters that league players were being paid. He was writing as a member of Tauranga Rugby League and challenged \u201cany member of the Rugby Union to produce evidence of proof of any monetary benefits received by players or officers of the Tauranga Rugby League. If this can be done I will donate \u00a350 to any charity benefit. <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Football Matters\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8102\n| date = 1922-09-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19220929.2.5.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. On October 14 Tauranga played a match on the Waihi Recreation Ground and lost 6-19 in front of a large attendance, Iles again leading the Tauranga team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Waihi-Tauranga League Match\n| page =2\n| publisher =Waihi Daily Telegraph, Volume XX, Issue 6741\n| date = 1922-10-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/WHDT19221016.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-11}}</ref>. These efforts to grow the game in the area, while somewhat remarkable, ultimately proved futile and Iles returned to the rugby union field the following season.\n\n===Back to Rugby Union===\nIn 1923 he played for Tauranga rugby team against Te Puke in Te Puke and then again in the return match in Tauranga. He was also turning out for the Cadets Old Boys senior side in the club competition <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football on Monday Next/Te Puke Representatives to Visit Tauranga\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8302\n| date = 1923-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230531.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He scored 2 tries for Cadets in an 11-8 win over Rangataua\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Local and General\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LI, Issue 8305\n| date = 1923-06-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19230605.2.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1924 he played for Tauranga against Te Puke in a Kusab's Cup match won by Tauranga 8-6\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Brilliant Game for Kusab's Cup\n| page = 5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LII, Issue 8633\n| date = 1924-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19240714.2.21\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played another match for them against Te Puke in June 1925, and captained Tauranga against [[Rangitaiki]] in 1925 to a 12-5 victory with Iles involved prominently throughout the match <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga v Te Puke\n| page =6\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LXII, Issue 19039\n| date = 1925-06-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19250609.2.10.3\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Match Won by Tauranga/Good Game Against Rangitaiki Team\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIII, Issue 8935\n| date = 1925-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250720.2.25\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the end of the rugby season he joined the Tauranga Rowing Club, being elected a member on 26 September at their AGM\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rowing Club/Annual General Meeting\n| page =5\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 8994\n| date = 1925-09-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19250926.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1926 Iles represented Tauranga against [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]]<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga v Hamilton\n| page = 15\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19373\n| date = 1926-07-07\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260707.2.159\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. He was playing for the Cadets Old Boys club this season\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Rugby Union Championships\n| page =4\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LIV, Issue 9179\n| date = 1929-05-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19260510.2.30\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. He played for Tauranga against Whakatane soon after<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Kusabs Cup Fixture\n| page = 8\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXIII, Issue 19387\n| date = 1926-07-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19260723.2.15\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The year was to end sadly for Iles though as his father Albert collapsed and died while playing bowls on the Tauranga South bowling green December 8, 1926. He was buried at Purewa Cemetery, in Meadowbank, Auckland<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Obituary/Mr Albert Iles\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LV, Issue 9359\n| date = 1926-12-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19261209.2.9\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nIn July 1929 George Iles brother Arthur (who was a councillor in Tauranga from 1925 to 1938 deputy mayor at one point)<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Mayors and Councillors\n| publisher = Tauranga Memories: Tauranga Local History\n| url =http://tauranga.kete.net.nz/tauranga_local_history/topics/show/2670-tauranga-mayors-and-councillors\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> wrote a letter to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] defending his brother as a player and coach in the Tauranga representative team. He was writing in reply to the same Mr. Phelan that his brother had written regarding years earlier. Arthur Iles said that he had been covering football in Tauranga for 10 years and \u201chas no recollection of ever noticing Mr Phelan in attendance at any annual general meeting of the Rugby Union\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Rugby Criticism\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10123\n| date = 1929-07-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290712.2.12.1\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nOn July 27, 1929 Tauranga beat Opotiki for the Hurinui Apanui Shield with Iles playing<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Apanui Shield/Tauranga Defeats Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10137\n| date = 1929-07-29\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290729.2.10\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. The Hurinui Apanui Shield was named after the famous Ngatiawa chief who had died in 1924 <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Death of Hurinui Apanui\n| page =5\n| publisher =King Country Chronicle, Volume XIX, Issue 1967\n| date = 1924-05-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/KCC19240524.2.23\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. A week later they defended it against Rotorua with Iles playing five eighth\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Shield Match/Rotorua V Tauranga\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10147\n| date = 1929-08-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290809.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Despite being 35 years of age by this point Iles was heavily involved in a 17-0 win playing with his \"characteristic cleverness\"\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Tauranga Union Retains Shield/Keen Rugby Game on Domain/Rotorua Defeated\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10149\n| date = 1929-08-12\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290812.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His younger brother Eric was playing alongside him in the backs through all of these matches. Eric would himself go on the represent the Bay of Plenty rugby team\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Management Committee\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles played again in the defence against Taupo on August 24 which they won 27-11 and again in early September against Opotiki <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Huinui Apanui Shield Game/Tauranga Defeats Taupo/A Good Margin\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10161\n| date = 1929-08-26\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290826.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Team to Play Opotiki\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10168\n| date = 1929-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290903.2.11\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. They drew the match 6-6 with a penalty after the full time bell which meant they retained the shield for the summer as it was the last challenge of the year\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Hurinui Apanui Shield Match/Spectacular Game Ends in Even Score\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10173\n| date = 1929-09-09\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290909.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. At the start of the 1930 season Iles was appointed the backs coach with J. Duncan coaching the forwards for the Tauranga team <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. His coaching career did not begin well with the team losing the match 3-6 to Te Puke, and the Hurinui Apanui Shield in the process <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Keen Game for the Te Hurinui Apanui Shield/Te Puke Defeats Tauranga by Six to Three\n| page = 3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10403\n| date = 1930-06-16\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300616.2.17\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nIles was a member of the Athletic Football Club from 1928 onwards with his brother Arthur on the management committee <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Athletic Club\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10049\n| date = 1929-04-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290415.2.12\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They had been named College Old Boys until 1928 when they changed to the Athletic name <ref>{{cite news\n| title =A Name Changed\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVI, Issue 9766\n| date = 1928-04-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19280423.2.6\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. Iles was playing for their senior team along with his brother Eric\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tomorrow's Games\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVII, Issue 10088\n| date = 1929-05-31\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19290531.2.8\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. In 1930 George had turned his hand to refereeing in the Jordan Cup for senior club teams\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Tauranga Unions Competitions/Jordan Cup-Seniors\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10382\n| date = 1930-05-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300521.2.13\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. However he was still playing, turning out for Athletic against Cadets in the Jordan Cup and scoring a try in a 6-9 loss\n<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Rugby Football/Tauranga Union's Cup Competitions\n| page =3\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LVIII, Issue 10415\n| date = 1930-06-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19300630.2.20\n| accessdate = 2020-04-10}}</ref>. By 1932 George had become the club captain and still writing letters to the [[Bay of Plenty Times]] <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Football Criticism\n| page =2\n| publisher =Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LXI, Issue 10905\n| date = 1932-09-03\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19320903.2.11.2\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Business Life==\nHe and his brother Arthur established a wool and hide exporting business based in Tauranga immediately after moving there in 1920 exporting \"hides, calf skins, sheepskins, wool, tallow, horsehair etc\" <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Frederick Iles\n| page = 12\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LXX, Issue 21452\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. They were based on Willow St., Tauranga with depots in [[Te Puke]], [[Whakatane]], and [[Taneatua]] and acted as agents for Wilson and Canham <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Iles Bros\n| page = 1\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume XLVIII, Issue 7349\n| date = 1920-03-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19200301.2.3.4\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==Death==\nGeorge Iles died on March 27 1933 one day before what would have been his 40th birthday, after suffering from a \u201csevere illness\u201d <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Mr. George Iles\n| page = 3\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 72\n| date = 1933-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330327.2.26\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>. His funeral was held on March 29 with a very large gathering present at the Holy Trinity Church. His pall-bearers were members of various football clubs, namely \u201cI. Tangitu (Maori Clubs), C. Cameron, J. Duncan and A. Tassell (Athletics Club), and W. Mansel and C. Haua (Cadets Old Boys)\u201d. The funeral was also attended by various members of Bay of Plenty organisations including the mayor of Tauranga and representatives of all the football clubs and over two hundred telegrams were received from all over the country <ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late Mr Geo. Iles/The Last Tribute\n| page = 2\n| publisher = Bay of Plenty Times, Volume LX, Issue 11078\n| date = 1933-03-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/BOPT19330330.2.14\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\nGeorge Iles was survived by his widow Grace Malya Iles, who he had wed in 1927, and two young sons<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Late G. F. Iles\n| page = 13\n| publisher = Auckland Star, Volume LXIV, Issue 73\n| date = 1933-03-28\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19330328.2.141\n| accessdate = 2020-04-08}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iles, George}}\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby league players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand national rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league team players]]\n[[Category:Newton Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Rugby league players from Christchurch]]\n[[Category:Bay of Plenty rugby union players]]\n", "name_user": "Yamis", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Iles"}
{"title_page": "Seema Tapakai", "text_new": "{{short description|2011 film by G.Nageswara Reddy}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Seema Tapakai\n| image          = Seema Tapakai poster.jpg\n| caption        = Movie Poster\n| director       = [[G.Nageswara Reddy]]\n| story          = G. Nageswara Reddy\n| starring       = [[Allari Naresh]]<br />[[Poorna]]<br />[[Sayaji Shinde]]<br />[[Jaya Prakash Reddy]]\n| music          = [[Vandemataram Srinivas]]\n| cinematography = Adusumilli Vijay Kumar\n| editing        = [[Kotagiri Venkateswara Rao]]\n| studio         = Wellfare Creations\n| distributor    = [[Dil Raju]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2011|05|13}}\n| runtime        = 128 min \n| country        = India\n| language       = Telugu\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Seema Tapakai''''' is a [[2011 in film|2011]] Indian [[Telugu language|Telugu]]-language [[comedy film]] written and directed by [[G.Nageswara Reddy]], produced by Dr. Vijaya Prasad Malla under Wellfare Creations banner and starring [[Allari Naresh]] and [[Poorna]] in lead roles. The film soundtrack was composed by [[Vandemataram Srinivas]] and cinematography was handled by Adusumilli Vijay Kumar. The dialogue of the movie was written by popular writer Marudhuri Raja. The screenplay was handled also by G Nageswara Reddy. This film marks the debut of actress [[Poorna]] in Telugu cinema. Seema Tapakai was released on 13 May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seematapakai - Telugu movie|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1946389/|publisher=IMDB|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nSri Krishna ([[Allari Naresh]]) is the son of a big businessman and multimillionaire, GK ([[Sayaji Shinde]]). His father is so rich that he hates even the smell of the poor, and despises anyone who talks about giving money as alms. Sri Krishna's family, too, doesn't mind the opulence they have. Coming from this family, he falls in love with Satya ([[Poorna]]), who thinks the rich become richer by exploiting the poor. In order to make Satya fall for him, Krishna starts acting as a poor chap, with a poor family. He buys his way out to show Satya that he helps the poor, and unintentionally becomes their savior of sorts. When Satya accepts his love, he recruits his family to help him convince her completely. So the rich father becomes a banana seller, rich mother becomes a bajji seller, etc. However, it turns out that Satya is the daughter of Nagineedu (Nagineedu) a factionist from Kurnool who has a rivalry with another faction leader Venkatappa([[Jaya Prakash Reddy]]). She urges her father to share his riches with his followers, an idea which his father doesn't take. But on knowing that she wants to marry a poor boy, he doesn't mind it. In order to get them married Krishna asks her father to act as a Head Master. Both families in their disguises respectively meet and arrange the marriage of Krishna and Satya. Faction leader Venkatappa attacks the family of GK to kill Nagineedu. Knowing the truth about Nagineedu, GK is angered and cancels the marriage. Krishna uses his brain to try to help resolve issues between Venkatappa and Nagineedu and also convinces his father GK for the marriage. In the end, the two factionists understand the value of life and they stop fighting. Both GK and Nagineedu once again agree upon Krishna's marriage.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Allari Naresh]] as Sri Krishna\n* [[Poorna]] as Satya\n* [[Sayaji Shinde]] as GK (Gurajada Krishnamurthy)\n* Sudha as Rajyalakshmi (GK's wife)\n* [[L.B. Sriram]] as Aravind Swamy\n* [[Brahmanandam]] as Melimbangaram\n* [[M. S. Narayana]] as GK's PA\n* [[Nagineedu]] as Nagineedu\n* [[Jaya Prakash Reddy]] as Venkatappa\n* [[Rao Ramesh]] as Narsimha\n* [[Vennela Kishore]] as Kishore\n* [[Ravi Prakash (Telugu actor)|Ravi Prakash]] as Manoj (GK's son)\n* [[Tirupathi Prakash]] as Servant\n* [[Surekha Vani]] as GK's daughter\n* [[Geetha Singh]] as Maid\n* [[Jeeva (Telugu actor)|Jeeva]]\n* [[Prabhakar (Telugu actor)|Prabhakar]]\n* [[Uttej]]\n{{colend}}\n\n== Crew ==\n* Banner: Wellfare Creations\n* Music: Sri Vasanth\n* Dialogues: Marudhuri Raja\n* Cinematography: Adusumilli Vijay Kumar\n* Fights: Ram-Laxman\n* Editing: [[Kotagiri Venkateswara Rao]]\n* Art: K.V. Subbarao\n* Audiographer: E. Radha Krishna\n* Lyrics: Bheems, [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy|Veturi]], Bhaskarabhatla, Chilakarekka Ganesh\n* Choreography: Brinda, Krishna Reddy, Prem Rakshith\n* Story: G Nageswara Reddy\n* Screenplay: G Nageswara Reddy\n* Direction: G Nageswara Reddy\n* Producer: Dr. Vijaya Prasad Malla\n* Theatrical release date: 13 May 2011\n\n==Production and Casting==\nThis movie was produced by Dr. Vijaya Prasad Malla, who is also an MLA in [[Andhra Pradesh]] legislative assembly. The director of this movie G Nageswara Reddy had previously worked with Allari Naresh in the movie [[Seema Sastri]] as director. He collaborated for the second time with [[Allari Naresh]] for this movie. Both Naresh and Nageswara Reddy are known for their comedy in movies. As expected this movie was a comedy entertainer. The movie was delayed due to the Telugu movie strike of 2011. This was Allari Naresh's second release in the year after Aha Na Pellanta. [[Poorna]] who acted in several Tamil and Malayalam movies in the past was cast for the role of Satya, daughter of a factionist. This is Poorna's first Telugu movie. Being a comedy movie, it features most of the Telugu comedians like [[L.B. Sriram]],  [[Brahmanandam]], [[M. S. Narayana]], [[Sayaji Shinde]], Rao ramesh, [[Jaya Prakash Reddy]], [[Jeeva (Telugu actor)|Jeeva]], [[Uttej]], [[Vennela Kishore]] and Geeta Singh. Famous dialogue Writer Marudhuri raja assisted Nageswara Reddy with the dialogues in the movie. Shooting of the movie began in 2010 and was completed in April 2011 and the movie was released in May 2011. Shooting was predominantly done in Hyderabad.\n\n==Release and Reception==\nThe movie was released in India and Overseas on 13 May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seema Tapakai in USA|url=http://www.idlebrain.com/usschedules/seematapakai.html|publisher=idlebrain|accessdate=11 January 2012}}</ref>  The movie was received with positive reviews. Suresh Kavirayani of Times of India gave a good 3 of 5 rating for the movie and said the movie was fun to watch with whole family.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kavirayani|first=Suresh|title=Seema Tapakai Review|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/telugu/Seema-Tapakai/movie-review/8320398.cms|publisher=Times of India|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref> Esskay from 123 Telugu gave a 3.5 of 5 rating for the movie and commented that the movie was the best entertainer of the season.<ref>{{cite web|author=Esskay|title=Seema Tapakai Review|url=http://www.123telugu.com/reviews/S/Seema_Tapakai/Seema_Tapakai_Review.html|publisher=123 Telugu|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref> Sunita Chowdary from Cinegoer gave a very positive review of the movie and said that it was a fun film for all that summer.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chowdary|first=Sunita|title=Seema Tapakai Review|url=http://www.cinegoer.com/telugu-cinema/sunitas-reviews/seema-tapakai-movie-review-130511.html|publisher=Cinegoer|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref> The movie fared very well at the box office and was declared a hit in the year 2011.\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Seema Tapakai\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Vandemataram Srinivas]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|2011|4|18}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Madhura Audio\n| producer   = [[Vandemataram Srinivas]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nAudio release of the film was held on 18 April 2011 in Hyderabad. The audio was released and distributed by Madhura Audio.<ref>{{cite web|title=seematapaki through madhura audio|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/65813.html|publisher=indiaglitz|accessdate=11 January 2012}}</ref>  The music of this movie was composed by Vandemataram Srinivas. The audio was well received. Bheems penned 2 songs in the movie while Bhaskarabhatla Ravikumar and Chilakarekka Ganesh penned one song each.<ref>{{cite web|title=seema tapakai audio release|url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/functions/audio-seematapakai.html|publisher=idlebrain|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> The famous song \"Akasamlo Oka Tara\" in the movie ''[[Simhasanam (1986 film)|Simhasanam]]'', written by legendary poet [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy|Veturi]] and music by [[Bappi Lahiri]] was remixed by Vandemataram Srinivas for this movie. The song was sung by [[Javed Ali]] and [[Sravana Bhargavi]].\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Artist(s)\n| title1 = Dheere Dheere Dille | lyrics1 = Bheems  | extra1 = [[N. C. Karunya|Karunya]], [[Geetha Madhuri]] | length1 = 4:25\n| title2 = Akasamlo Okatara | lyrics2 = [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy|Veturi]] | extra2 = [[Javed Ali]], [[Sravana Bhargavi]] | length2 = 4:40\n| title3 = I Love U Baby | lyrics3 = Bhaskarabhatla Ravikumar | extra3 = Viswa, [[Sravana Bhargavi]] | length3 = 4:15\n| title4 = Dheere Dheere Dille | lyrics4 = Bheems | extra4 = [[N. C. Karunya|Karunya]], [[Geetha Madhuri]] | length4 = 4:25\n| title5 = Kandi Chenu | lyrics5 = Chilakarekka Ganesh | extra5 = [[Vedala Hemachandra|Hemachandra]], [[Singer Usha|Usha]], Noyal | length5 = 4:01\n}}\n\n==Remake==\nThe film was remade into [[Bollywood|Hindi]] as ''[[Ajab Gazabb Love]]''. Directed by [[Sanjay Gadhvi]], the film stars [[Jackky Bhagnani]] and [[Nidhi Subbaiah]] in lead roles.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jackky Bhagnani to star in Seema Tapakai remake|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/1425577/Jackky-Bhagnani-to-star-in-Seema-Tapakai-remake|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|1946389|Seema Tapakai}}\n{{G. Nageswara Reddy}}\n[[Category:2011 films]]\n[[Category:Telugu-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Vandemataram Srinivas]]\n[[Category:Telugu films remade in other languages]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2011 film by G.Nageswara Reddy}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Seema Tapakai\n| image          = Seema Tapakai poster.jpg\n| caption        = Movie Poster\n| director       = [[G.Nageswara Reddy]]\n| story          = G. Nageswara Reddy\n| starring       = [[Allari Naresh]]<br />[[Poorna]]<br />[[Sayaji Shinde]]<br />[[Jaya Prakash Reddy]]\n| music          = [[Vandemataram Srinivas]]\n| cinematography = Adusumilli Vijay Kumar\n| editing        = [[Kotagiri Venkateswara Rao]]\n| studio         = Wellfare Creations\n| distributor    = [[Dil Raju]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2011|05|13}}\n| runtime        = 128 min \n| country        = India\n| language       = Telugu\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Seema Tapakai''''' is a [[2011 in film|2011]] Indian [[Telugu language|Telugu]]-language [[comedy film]] written and directed by [[G.Nageswara Reddy]], produced by Dr. Vijaya Prasad Malla under Wellfare Creations banner and starring [[Allari Naresh]] and [[Poorna]] in lead roles. The film soundtrack was composed by [[Vandemataram Srinivas]] and cinematography was handled by Adusumilli Vijay Kumar. The dialogue of the movie was written by popular writer Marudhuri Raja. The screenplay was handled also by G Nageswara Reddy. This film marks the debut of actress [[Poorna]] in Telugu cinema. Seema Tapakai was released on 13 May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seematapakai - Telugu movie|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1946389/|publisher=IMDB|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nSri Krishna ([[Allari Naresh]]) is the son of a big businessman and multimillionaire, GK ([[Sayaji Shinde]]). His father is so rich that he hates even the smell of the poor, and despises anyone who talks about giving money as alms. Sri Krishna's family, too, doesn't mind the opulence they have. Coming from this family, he falls in love with Satya ([[Poorna]]), who thinks the rich become richer by exploiting the poor. In order to make Satya fall for him, Krishna starts acting as a poor chap, with a poor family. He buys his way out to show Satya that he helps the poor, and unintentionally becomes their savior of sorts. When Satya accepts his love, he recruits his family to help him convince her completely. So the rich father becomes a banana seller, rich mother becomes a bajji seller, etc. However, it turns out that Satya is the daughter of Nagineedu (Nagineedu) a factionist from Kurnool who has a rivalry with another faction leader Venkatappa([[Jaya Prakash Reddy]]). She urges her father to share his riches with his followers, an idea which his father doesn't take. But on knowing that she wants to get married to a poor boy, he doesn't mind it. In order to get them married Krishna asks her father to act as a Head Master. Both families in their disguises respectively meet and arrange the marriage of Krishna and Satya. Faction leader Venkatappa attacks the family of GK to kill Nagineedu. Knowing the truth about Nagineedu, GK is angered and cancels the marriage. Krishna uses his brain to try to help resolve issues between Venkatappa and Nagineedu and also convinces his father GK for the marriage. At the End, the two factionists understand the value of life and they stop fighting. Both GK and Nagineedu once again agree upon Krishna's marriage.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Allari Naresh]] as Sri Krishna\n* [[Poorna]] as Satya\n* [[Sayaji Shinde]] as GK (Gurajada Krishnamurthy)\n* Sudha as Rajyalakshmi (GK's wife)\n* [[L.B. Sriram]] as Aravind Swamy\n* [[Brahmanandam]] as Melimbangaram\n* [[M. S. Narayana]] as GK's PA\n* [[Nagineedu]] as Nagineedu\n* [[Jaya Prakash Reddy]] as Venkatappa\n* [[Rao Ramesh]] as Narsimha\n* [[Vennela Kishore]] as Kishore\n* [[Ravi Prakash (Telugu actor)|Ravi Prakash]] as Manoj (GK's son)\n* [[Tirupathi Prakash]] as Servant\n* [[Surekha Vani]] as GK's daughter\n* [[Geetha Singh]] as Maid\n* [[Jeeva (Telugu actor)|Jeeva]]\n* [[Prabhakar (Telugu actor)|Prabhakar]]\n* [[Uttej]]\n{{colend}}\n\n== Crew ==\n* Banner: Wellfare Creations\n* Music: Sri Vasanth\n* Dialogues: Marudhuri Raja\n* Cinematography: Adusumilli Vijay Kumar\n* Fights: Ram-Laxman\n* Editing: [[Kotagiri Venkateswara Rao]]\n* Art: K.V. Subbarao\n* Audiographer: E. Radha Krishna\n* Lyrics: Bheems, [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy|Veturi]], Bhaskarabhatla, Chilakarekka Ganesh\n* Choreography: Brinda, Krishna Reddy, Prem Rakshith\n* Story: G Nageswara Reddy\n* Screenplay: G Nageswara Reddy\n* Direction: G Nageswara Reddy\n* Producer: Dr. Vijaya Prasad Malla\n* Theatrical release date: 13 May 2011\n\n==Production and Casting==\nThis movie was produced by Dr. Vijaya Prasad Malla, who is also an MLA in [[Andhra Pradesh]] legislative assembly. The director of this movie G Nageswara Reddy had previously worked with Allari Naresh in the movie [[Seema Sastri]] as director. He collaborated for the second time with [[Allari Naresh]] for this movie. Both Naresh and Nageswara Reddy are known for their comedy in movies. As expected this movie was a comedy entertainer. The movie was delayed due to the Telugu movie strike of 2011. This was Allari Naresh's second release in the year after Aha Na Pellanta. [[Poorna]] who acted in several Tamil and Malayalam movies in the past was cast for the role of Satya, daughter of a factionist. This is Poorna's first Telugu movie. Being a comedy movie, it features most of the Telugu comedians like [[L.B. Sriram]],  [[Brahmanandam]], [[M. S. Narayana]], [[Sayaji Shinde]], Rao ramesh, [[Jaya Prakash Reddy]], [[Jeeva (Telugu actor)|Jeeva]], [[Uttej]], [[Vennela Kishore]] and Geeta Singh. Famous dialogue Writer Marudhuri raja assisted Nageswara Reddy with the dialogues in the movie. Shooting of the movie began in 2010 and was completed in April 2011 and the movie was released in May 2011. Shooting was predominantly done in Hyderabad.\n\n==Release and Reception==\nThe movie was released in India and Overseas on 13 May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seema Tapakai in USA|url=http://www.idlebrain.com/usschedules/seematapakai.html|publisher=idlebrain|accessdate=11 January 2012}}</ref>  The movie was received with positive reviews. Suresh Kavirayani of Times of India gave a good 3 of 5 rating for the movie and said the movie was fun to watch with whole family.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kavirayani|first=Suresh|title=Seema Tapakai Review|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/telugu/Seema-Tapakai/movie-review/8320398.cms|publisher=Times of India|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref> Esskay from 123 Telugu gave a 3.5 of 5 rating for the movie and commented that the movie was the best entertainer of the season.<ref>{{cite web|author=Esskay|title=Seema Tapakai Review|url=http://www.123telugu.com/reviews/S/Seema_Tapakai/Seema_Tapakai_Review.html|publisher=123 Telugu|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref> Sunita Chowdary from Cinegoer gave a very positive review of the movie and said that it was a fun film for all that summer.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chowdary|first=Sunita|title=Seema Tapakai Review|url=http://www.cinegoer.com/telugu-cinema/sunitas-reviews/seema-tapakai-movie-review-130511.html|publisher=Cinegoer|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref> The movie fared very well at the box office and was declared a hit in the year 2011.\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Seema Tapakai\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Vandemataram Srinivas]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|2011|4|18}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film soundtrack]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Madhura Audio\n| producer   = [[Vandemataram Srinivas]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nAudio release of the film was held on 18 April 2011 in Hyderabad. The audio was released and distributed by Madhura Audio.<ref>{{cite web|title=seematapaki through madhura audio|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/65813.html|publisher=indiaglitz|accessdate=11 January 2012}}</ref>  The music of this movie was composed by Vandemataram Srinivas. The audio was well received. Bheems penned 2 songs in the movie while Bhaskarabhatla Ravikumar and Chilakarekka Ganesh penned one song each.<ref>{{cite web|title=seema tapakai audio release|url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/functions/audio-seematapakai.html|publisher=idlebrain|accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> The famous song \"Akasamlo Oka Tara\" in the movie ''[[Simhasanam (1986 film)|Simhasanam]]'', written by legendary poet [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy|Veturi]] and music by [[Bappi Lahiri]] was remixed by Vandemataram Srinivas for this movie. The song was sung by [[Javed Ali]] and [[Sravana Bhargavi]].\n\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column    = Artist(s)\n| title1 = Dheere Dheere Dille | lyrics1 = Bheems  | extra1 = [[N. C. Karunya|Karunya]], [[Geetha Madhuri]] | length1 = 4:25\n| title2 = Akasamlo Okatara | lyrics2 = [[Veturi Sundararama Murthy|Veturi]] | extra2 = [[Javed Ali]], [[Sravana Bhargavi]] | length2 = 4:40\n| title3 = I Love U Baby | lyrics3 = Bhaskarabhatla Ravikumar | extra3 = Viswa, [[Sravana Bhargavi]] | length3 = 4:15\n| title4 = Dheere Dheere Dille | lyrics4 = Bheems | extra4 = [[N. C. Karunya|Karunya]], [[Geetha Madhuri]] | length4 = 4:25\n| title5 = Kandi Chenu | lyrics5 = Chilakarekka Ganesh | extra5 = [[Vedala Hemachandra|Hemachandra]], [[Singer Usha|Usha]], Noyal | length5 = 4:01\n}}\n\n==Remake==\nThe film was remade into [[Bollywood|Hindi]] as ''[[Ajab Gazabb Love]]''. Directed by [[Sanjay Gadhvi]], the film stars [[Jackky Bhagnani]] and [[Nidhi Subbaiah]] in lead roles.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jackky Bhagnani to star in Seema Tapakai remake|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/1425577/Jackky-Bhagnani-to-star-in-Seema-Tapakai-remake|publisher=Bollywood Hungama|accessdate=17 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|1946389|Seema Tapakai}}\n{{G. Nageswara Reddy}}\n[[Category:2011 films]]\n[[Category:Telugu-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Vandemataram Srinivas]]\n[[Category:Telugu films remade in other languages]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seema_Tapakai"}
